            "2-4": {
                icon: "fa-border-all",
                title: "Position (Relative, Absolute, Fixed)",
                html: `<h1>Week 2, Day 4: Practical Layout Basics - Position (Relative, Absolute, Fixed). </h1>
    <p>Today we'll learn how to position elements intentionally and create practical layouts.</p>
    
    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Theater Stage üé≠</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Static</b> = Actors standing in default positions</li>
            <li><b>Relative</b> = Actor moves from their marked spot</li>
            <li><b>Absolute</b> = Actor ignores others, uses stage coordinates</li>
            <li><b>Fixed</b> = Actor glued to one spot, even if stage moves</li>
            <li><b>Sticky</b> = Actor stays until scene changes, then moves</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>CSS Positioning - Five Positions</li>
        <li>Centering Techniques</li>
        <li>Z-index & Stacking Context</li>
        <li>Overflow Property</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>In-Depth Explanation</h3>
    
    <b>a. CSS Positioning - Five Positions</b><br/>
    
    <b>1. Static (Default) - "Normal Flow"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            div {
                position: static;   /* Default */
            }
        </pre>
        <small>- Normal document flow</small>
        <small>- Ignores top/left/right/bottom properties</small><br/>
        <small><b>Analogy:</b> People standing in a line</small>
    </div>
    
    <b>2. Relative - "Move From Your Spot"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            div {
                position: relative;
                top: 20px;              /* Move down 20px FROM original position */
                left: 30px;             /* Move right 30px FROM original position */
            }
        </pre>
        <small>- Still in normal flow (others see it in original position)</small><br/>
        <small>- Creates a new positioning context for absolute children</small><br/>
        <small><b>Analogy:</b> Taking one step from your marked spot on stage</small>
    </div>
    
    <b>3. Absolute - "Free Floating"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            div {
                position: absolute;
                top: 0;
                left: 0;
            }
        </pre>
        <small>- Removed from normal flow (others act like it's not there)</small><br/>
        <small>- Positions relative to nearest positioned ancestor</small><br/>
        <small>- If no positioned ancestor, uses document body</small><br/>
        <small><b>Analogy:</b> Flying above the stage, ignoring other actors</small>
    </div>
    
    <b>4. Fixed - "Window Sticker"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            nav {
                position: fixed;
                top: 0;
                left: 0;
                width: 100%;
            }
        </pre>
        <small>- Removed from normal flow</small><br/>
        <small>- Positions relative to viewport (browser window)</small><br/>
        <small>- Stays in place during scrolling</small><br/>
        <small><b>Analogy:</b> Sign glued to theater window</small>
    </div>
    
    <b>5. Sticky - "Temporary Fixed"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            th {
                position: sticky;
                top: 0;
            }
        </pre>
        <small>- Starts as relative, becomes fixed when scrolled past</small><br/>
        <small>- Needs a threshold (top, bottom, etc.)</small><br/>
        <small><b>Analogy:</b> Actor who stays on stage until cue, then leaves</small>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>b. Positioning Demo: Layered Elements</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px; position: relative; height: 250px;">
        <div style="background-color: lightgreen; padding: 10px; margin: 10px; border: 2px solid darkgreen;">Static (Green)</div>
        <div style="position: relative; background-color: lightblue; padding: 10px; margin: 10px; border: 2px solid darkblue; top: 30px; left: 50px;">Relative (Blue) - moved</div>
        <div style="position: absolute; background-color: lightcoral; padding: 10px; border: 2px solid darkred; top: 100px; right: 20px;">Absolute (Red)</div>
        <div style="position: fixed; background-color: lavender; padding: 10px; border: 2px solid purple; bottom: 20px; right: 20px;">Fixed (Purple)</div>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>c. Centering Techniques - The "Holy Grail"</b><br/>
    
    <b>1. Horizontal Centering</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            /* Text/Inline elements */
            .center-text {
                text-align: center;
            }
            /* Block elements with known width */
            .center-block {
                width: 300px;
                margin: 0 auto; /* Equal left/right margins */
            }
            /* Unknown width elements */
            .center-unknown {
                display: table;
                margin: 0 auto;
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>2. Vertical Centering (Tricky!)</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            /* Single line of text */
            .center-text-vertical {
                height: 100px;
                line-height: 100px;         /* Match height */
            }
            /* Modern: Flexbox (preview) */
            .center-flex {
                display: flex;
                align-items: center;        /* Vertical */
                justify-content: center;    /* Horizontal */
                height: 300px;
            }
            /* Absolute positioning */
            .center-absolute {
                position: relative;
                height: 300px;
            }
            .center-absolute div {
                position: absolute;
                top: 50%;
                left: 50%;
                transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Centering Flowchart:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px; font-family: monospace;">
        Want to center something?<br/>
        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Is it text? ‚Üí text-align: center<br/>
        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Is it a block with fixed width? ‚Üí margin: 0 auto<br/>
        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Need both directions? ‚Üí Flexbox!<br/>
        ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Need old browser support? ‚Üí Absolute + transform
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>d. Z-index & Stacking Context - The "Layer Cake"</b><br/>
    
    <b>What is z-index?</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <small>- Controls vertical stacking order</small><br/>
        <small>- Higher number = closer to viewer</small><br/>
        <small>- Only works on positioned elements (relative, absolute, fixed)</small>
    </div>
    
    <div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px; position: relative;">
        <div style="position: relative; background-color: #ffcccc; padding: 20px; margin: 10px; z-index: 1;">Box 1 (z-index: 1)</div>
        <div style="position: relative; background-color: #ccccff; padding: 20px; margin: -40px 0 0 50px; z-index: 2;">Box 2 (z-index: 2) - On top!</div>
    </div>
    
    <b>Stacking Context Rules:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        1. Root element (html) creates first context<br/>
        2. Positioned elements with z-index create new contexts<br/>
        3. Children can't escape parent's stacking context<br/>
        4. Order (from bottom to top):<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Background/borders of root<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Non-positioned blocks<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Positioned blocks (by HTML order)<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Positioned blocks with z-index
    </div>
    
    <b>Common Problem:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            &lt;div class="parent" style="position: relative; z-index: 1;"&gt;
                &lt;div class="child" style="position: absolute; z-index: 9999;"&gt;
                    Still behind other elements at root level!
                &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;div class="other" style="position: relative; z-index: 2;"&gt;
                This covers the child, even with z-index: 9999!
            &lt;/div&gt;
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>e. Overflow Property - "When Content Overflows"</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            div {
                width: 200px;
                height: 100px;
            }
            /* Options: */
            .visible { overflow: visible; }         /* Default - spills out */
            .hidden  { overflow: hidden;  }          /* Cut off excess */
            .scroll  { overflow: scroll;  }          /* Always show scrollbars */
            .auto    { overflow: auto;    }         /* Scrollbars only if needed */
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Overflow variants:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        - <code>overflow-x</code>: Horizontal only<br/>
        - <code>overflow-y</code>: Vertical only<br/>
        - <code>text-overflow: ellipsis</code>: "..." for overflowing text
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <h3>Hands-On Exercise: Build a Navigation Bar</h3>
    <b>Task:</b> Create a fixed navigation bar with dropdowns<br/><br/>
    
    <b>Requirements:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        1. Fixed position at top<br/>
        2. Logo on left, menu items on right<br/>
        3. Dropdown menu on hover<br/>
        4. Centered content below nav<br/>
        5. Proper z-index for dropdowns
    </div>
    
    <b>HTML Structure:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            &lt;nav class="navbar"&gt;
                &lt;div class="logo"&gt;MySite&lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;ul class="nav-menu"&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li class="dropdown"&gt;
                        &lt;a href="#"&gt;Services ‚ñæ&lt;/a&gt;
                        &lt;ul class="dropdown-menu"&gt;
                            &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Web Design&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
                            &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Development&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
                            &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;SEO&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
                        &lt;/ul&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="#"&gt;Contact&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ul&gt;
            &lt;/nav&gt;
            &lt;main class="content"&gt;
                &lt;h1&gt;Welcome to Our Website&lt;/h1&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;This content should be centered below the navbar.&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/main&gt;
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>CSS Challenge:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Step 1:</b> Make navbar fixed at top with full width<br/>
        <b>Step 2:</b> Use display: flex for horizontal layout<br/>
        <b>Step 3:</b> Position dropdown absolutely under "Services"<br/>
        <b>Step 4:</b> Use z-index to ensure dropdown appears above content<br/>
        <b>Step 5:</b> Center the main content using margin: 0 auto<br/>
        <b>Step 6:</b> Add padding-top to main to account for fixed navbar
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>
    
    <b>Mistake 1: Forgetting positioning context</b>
    <div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            /* WRONG */
            .parent {
                /* No position set */
            }
            .child {
                position: absolute;
                top: 0;
                /* Will position relative to document, not parent! */
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Mistake 2: z-index not working</b>
    <div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            /* WRONG */
            div {
                z-index: 10;    /* Won't work without position! */
            }
            /* RIGHT */
            div {
                position: relative;
                z-index: 10;    /* Now it works! */
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Mistake 3: Overusing absolute positioning</b>
    <div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            /* WRONG - makes layout fragile */
            .everything {
                position: absolute;
                top: ...; left: ...;
            }
            /* BETTER - use for specific elements only */
            .dropdown, .tooltip {
                position: absolute;
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment: Complete Layout Challenge</h4>
