            "6-3": {
                icon: "fa-camera-retro",
                title: "Photo Manipulation for Web",
                html: `<h1>Week 6, Day 3: Photo Manipulation for Web</h1>
    <p>Today we'll learn how to edit and optimize photos specifically for web use, including background removal, filters, and color correction.</p>
    
    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Photo Darkroom vs Digital Editing üñºÔ∏è</b><br/>
        
        Background Removal: Cutting out subject from photo backdrop<br/>
        Filters & Effects: Applying different "lens filters"<br/>
        Color Correction: Adjusting brightness/contrast like in darkroom<br/>
        Image Optimization: Compressing without losing quality<br/>
        Responsive Images: Different crops for different screens<br/>
        File Formats: Choosing right "film" for the job<br/>
        Batch Processing: Editing multiple photos at once
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Background Removal Techniques</li>
        <li>Color Correction & Adjustment</li>
        <li>Applying Filters & Effects</li>
        <li>Image Optimization Workflow</li>
        <li>Batch Processing Tools</li>
        <li>CSS Filters & Blend Modes</li>
        <li>Creating Image Assets for Web</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>In-Depth Explanation</h3>
    
    <b>a. Background Removal Techniques</b>
    
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Why Remove Backgrounds?</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Create transparent PNGs for logos, products<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Composite images together<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Improve visual consistency<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Reduce visual clutter<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Create custom graphics<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Improve loading with solid colors vs complex backgrounds<br/><br/>
        
        <b>Common Use Cases:</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ E-commerce product photos<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Team member portraits<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Logo placement on different backgrounds<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Marketing materials<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Social media graphics
    </div>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
        <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <b>Manual Tools (Precision):</b><br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Pen Tool:</b> Most precise, best for clean edges<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Polygonal Lasso:</b> Good for geometric shapes<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Magic Wand:</b> Quick for solid color backgrounds<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Quick Selection:</b> AI-assisted, good for complex edges<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Layer Masks:</b> Non-destructive editing<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Refine Edge:</b> For hair, fur, transparent objects<br/><br/>
            
            <b>Best for:</b> Professional work, complex subjects, precise edges
        </div>
        
        <div style="background-color: #fff0f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <b>Automatic Tools (Speed):</b><br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Remove.bg:</b> AI-powered, one-click removal<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Photoshop Select Subject:</b> Built-in AI selection<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Canva Background Remover:</b> Free tool in browser<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>GIMP Foreground Select:</b> Free alternative<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Online Tools:</b> Photopea, Pixlr, LunaPic<br/><br/>
            
            <b>Best for:</b> Quick edits, bulk processing, simple subjects<br/><br/>
            
            <b>Limitations:</b> May struggle with fine details, hair, transparent objects
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Step-by-Step Background Removal (Photoshop/GIMP):</b><br/>
        <pre>
            <b>Method 1: Pen Tool (Precision)</b>
            1. Select Pen Tool (P)
            2. Zoom in to 200-300%
            3. Click to create anchor points around subject
            4. Complete path (connect last point to first)
            5. Right-click path ‚Üí Make Selection (Feather: 0.5-1px)
            6. Layer ‚Üí Layer Mask ‚Üí Reveal Selection
            7. Refine mask edges if needed
            
            <b>Method 2: Select Subject (AI)</b>
            1. Select ‚Üí Subject (Photoshop)
            2. Select ‚Üí Select Subject (GIMP with plugin)
            3. Refine selection with Select and Mask tool
            4. Adjust edge detection, smoothness, contrast
            5. Output to: Layer Mask
            6. Clean up mask with brush tool
            
            <b>Method 3: Quick Selection + Refine Edge</b>
            1. Select Quick Selection Tool (W)
            2. Brush over subject
            3. Hold Alt to subtract from selection
            4. Select ‚Üí Select and Mask
            5. Use Refine Edge Brush for tricky areas (hair, etc.)
            6. Output as New Layer with Layer Mask
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>b. Color Correction & Adjustment</b>
    
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Essential Color Adjustments:</b><br/>
        <pre>
            <b>1. Levels Adjustment</b>
            ‚Ä¢ Adjusts shadows, midtones, highlights
            ‚Ä¢ Fixes exposure problems
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Levels
            ‚Ä¢ GIMP: Colors ‚Üí Levels
            
            <b>2. Curves Adjustment</b>
            ‚Ä¢ More precise than Levels
            ‚Ä¢ Adjust specific tonal ranges
            ‚Ä¢ Create S-curve for contrast
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Curves
            
            <b>3. Hue/Saturation</b>
            ‚Ä¢ Adjust overall or specific color ranges
            ‚Ä¢ Desaturate for black & white
            ‚Ä¢ Boost colors for vibrancy
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Hue/Saturation
            
            <b>4. Color Balance</b>
            ‚Ä¢ Adjust color casts (too blue, yellow, etc.)
            ‚Ä¢ Separate adjustments for shadows/midtones/highlights
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Color Balance
            
            <b>5. Brightness/Contrast</b>
            ‚Ä¢ Simple adjustment
            ‚Ä¢ Use Curves for more control
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Brightness/Contrast
            
            <b>6. Vibrance vs Saturation</b>
            ‚Ä¢ Vibrance: Smart saturation (protects skin tones)
            ‚Ä¢ Saturation: All colors equally
            ‚Ä¢ Photoshop: Image ‚Üí Adjustments ‚Üí Vibrance
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Color Correction Workflow:</b><br/>
        1. <b>Analyze Image:</b> Check histogram, identify problems<br/>
        2. <b>Set Black/White Points:</b> Use Levels to define darkest/lightest areas<br/>
        3. <b>Adjust Exposure:</b> Fix too dark/bright areas<br/>
        4. <b>Correct Color Cast:</b> Remove unwanted color tints<br/>
        5. <b>Enhance Colors:</b> Adjust saturation/vibrance<br/>
        6. <b>Sharpen:</b> Apply subtle sharpening if needed<br/>
        7. <b>Save for Web:</b> Export optimized version<br/><br/>
        
        <b>Pro Tips:</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Use adjustment layers (non-destructive)<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Work on copy of original image<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Calibrate your monitor regularly<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Use reference images for color matching<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Consider final output (web vs print different)
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>c. Filters & Effects for Web</b>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
        <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <b>Popular Web Image Effects:</b><br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Blur:</b> Background blur, depth of field<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Vignette:</b> Darken edges, focus attention<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Sepia/Toned:</b> Vintage/retro look<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Black & White:</b> Classic, dramatic<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Duotone:</b> Two-color effect<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Grain/Noise:</b> Film-like texture<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Glow:</b> Soft edges, dreamy look<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Shadow/Drop Shadow:</b> Depth and separation<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Border/Frame:</b> Define image edges<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ <b>Text Overlay:</b> Captions, watermarks<br/><br/>
            
            <b>Modern Trends:</b><br/>
            ‚Ä¢ Gradient overlays<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ Color grading (teal/orange, etc.)<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ Double exposure<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ Glitch effects<br/>
            ‚Ä¢ Geometric patterns
        </div>
        
        <div style="background-color: #fff0f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <b>CSS Image Filters:</b><br/>
            <pre>
                /* Basic CSS filters */
                .filtered-image {
                    filter: blur(5px);
                    filter: brightness(150%);
                    filter: contrast(200%);
                    filter: grayscale(100%);
                    filter: hue-rotate(90deg);
                    filter: invert(100%);
                    filter: opacity(50%);
                    filter: saturate(200%);
                    filter: sepia(100%);
                
                    /* Multiple filters */
                    filter: grayscale(50%) blur(2px) brightness(110%);
                
                    /* Drop shadow */
                    filter: drop-shadow(5px 5px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5));
                }
                
                /* Background blend modes */
                .blend-image {
                    background-image: url('photo.jpg'), linear-gradient(45deg, #ff6b6b, #4ecdc4);
                    background-blend-mode: multiply;
                }
                
                /* Mix blend mode */
                .text-overlay {
                    mix-blend-mode: overlay;
                }
            </pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Creating Common Effects:</b><br/>
        <pre>
            <b>1. Duotone Effect (CSS)</b>
            .duotone {
                ;filter: grayscale(100%) contrast(150%) brightness(90%);
                ;background-blend-mode: multiply;
                ;background-image: url('photo.jpg'), linear-gradient(45deg, #ff6b6b, #4ecdc4);
            }
            
            <b>2. Vignette Effect (CSS)</b>
            .vignette {
                ;position: relative;
            }
            .vignette::after {
                ;content: '';
                ;position: absolute;
                ;top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; bottom: 0;
                ;background: radial-gradient(circle at center, transparent 40%, rgba(0,0,0,0.5) 100%);
                ;pointer-events: none;
            }
            
            <b>3. Image Overlay (CSS)</b>
            .image-overlay {
                ;position: relative;
                ;background: linear-gradient(45deg, #ff6b6b, #4ecdc4);
            }
            .image-overlay img {
                ;mix-blend-mode: multiply;
                ;opacity: 0.8;
            }
            
            <b>4. Glitch Effect (CSS)</b>
            @keyframes glitch {
                ;0% { transform: translate(0); }
                ;20% { transform: translate(-2px, 2px); }
                ;40% { transform: translate(-2px, -2px); }
                ;60% { transform: translate(2px, 2px); }
                ;80% { transform: translate(2px, -2px); }
                ;100% { transform: translate(0); }
            }
            .glitch {
                ;animation: glitch 0.5s infinite;
                ;filter: hue-rotate(90deg);
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
