                "title": "Control Flow Fundamentals",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 2: Control Flow Fundamentals</h1>\n<p>Master conditional statements and loops - the building blocks of programming logic and decision-making.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: Traffic Control System üö¶</b><br/>\n    <ul style=\"margin-top: 10px;\">\n        <li><b>if/else statements</b> = Traffic lights making decisions</li>\n        <li><b>switch statements</b> = Multi-lane highway exits</li>\n        <li><b>Loops</b> = Circular roundabouts</li>\n        <li><b>Conditions</b> = Road signs and rules</li>\n        <li><b>Logic</b> = Traffic flow patterns</li>\n    </ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Key Topics</h3>\n<ul>\n    <li>Conditional Statements (if/else)</li>\n    <li>Switch Statements</li>\n    <li>Comparison & Logical Operators</li>\n    <li>Loops (for, while, do-while)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Conditional Statements: Making Decisions</h3>\n\n<b>1. Basic if/else Structure</b><br/>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        if (condition) {<br/>\n         // Code runs if condition is true<br/>\n        } else {<br/>\n          // Code runs if condition is false<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>2. Comparison Operators</b>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;\">\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Operator</th>\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Meaning</th>\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Example</th>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>===</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Strict equality</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>5 === 5</pre> (true)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f9f9f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>!==</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Strict inequality</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>5 !== '5'</pre> (true)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>></pre>, <pre><</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Greater/Less than</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>10 > 5</pre> (true)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f9f9f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>>=</pre>, <pre><=</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Greater/Less or equal</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>5 >= 5</pre> (true)</td>\n    </tr>\n</table>\n\n<b>3. Logical Operators (AND, OR, NOT)</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // AND (&&) - Both must be true<br/>\n        if (age >= 18 && hasLicense) {<br/>\n          console.log(\"Can drive\");<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // OR (||) - At least one must be true<br/>\n        if (isMember || hasCoupon) {<br/>\n           console.log(\"Discount applied\");<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // NOT (!) - Reverses the boolean<br/>\n        if (!isLoggedIn) {<br/>\n            console.log(\"Please log in\");<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>4. Switch Statements (Multiple Conditions)</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let day = \"Monday\";<br/><br/>\n        switch (day) {<br/>\n          case \"Monday\":<br/>\n              console.log(\"Start of work week\");<br/>\n                break;<br/>\n           case \"Friday\":<br/>\n                console.log(\"Weekend is near!\");<br/>\n              break;<br/>\n          default:<br/>\n              console.log(\"Regular day\");<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Loops: Repeating Actions</h3>\n\n<b>5. For Loop (Definite Iteration)</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Basic structure<br/>\n        for (initialization; condition; increment) {<br/>\n          // Code to repeat<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // Count from 1 to 5<br/>\n        for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {<br/>\n         console.log(\"Count: \" + i);<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // Output: Count: 1, Count: 2, Count: 3, Count: 4, Count: 5\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>6. While Loop (Condition-Based)</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Check condition BEFORE each iteration<br/>\n        let count = 1;<br/><br/>\n        while (count <= 5) {<br/>\n           console.log(\"While count: \" + count);<br/>\n         count++;<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>7. Do-While Loop (Execute at Least Once)</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Execute FIRST, then check condition<br/>\n        let userInput;<br/><br/>\n        do {<br/>\n            userInput = prompt(\"Enter 'yes' to continue:\");<br/>\n        } while (userInput !== \"yes\");<br/><br/>\n        console.log(\"Thank you!\");\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Practical Examples</h3>\n\n<b>Example 1: User Authentication</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let username = \"admin\";<br/>\n        let password = \"12345\";<br/>\n        let attempts = 3;<br/><br/>\n        while (attempts > 0) {<br/>\n          let inputUser = prompt(\"Username:\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;let inputPass = prompt(\"Password:\");<br/><br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;if (inputUser === username && inputPass === password) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Login successful!\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;break;<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;} else {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;attempts--;<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(`Incorrect. ${attempts} attempts remaining.`);<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>Example 2: Number Guessing Game</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let secretNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10) + 1;<br/>\n        let guess;<br/><br/>\n        do {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;guess = parseInt(prompt(\"Guess a number between 1-10:\"));<br/><br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;if (guess < secretNumber) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Too low! Try again.\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;} else if (guess > secretNumber) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Too high! Try again.\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>\n        } while (guess !== secretNumber);<br/><br/>\n        console.log(\"Congratulations! You guessed it!\");\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Common Mistakes</h3>\n\n<b>Mistake 1: Infinite Loops</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // WRONG - Infinite loop!<br/>\n        let i = 0;<br/>\n        while (i < 5) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(i);<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Forgot to increment i!<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // RIGHT<br/>\n        let i = 0;<br/>\n        while (i < 5) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(i);<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;i++;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Increment counter\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>Mistake 2: Missing Break in Switch</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // WRONG - Falls through<br/>\n        switch (color) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;case \"red\":<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Stop\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Missing break!<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;case \"green\":<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Go\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;break;<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // RIGHT<br/>\n        switch (color) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;case \"red\":<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\"Stop\");<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;break;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Add break!\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<hr/>\n\n<div class=\"assignment-box\">\n    <h4>Assignment: Shopping Cart Logic</h4>\n    <p>Create a shopping cart system using control flow:</p>\n    \n    <div style=\"background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n        <b>Requirements:</b><br/>\n        1. Ask user for item quantity and price<br/>\n        2. Calculate subtotal<br/>\n        3. Apply discounts based on rules:<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- 10% off for orders over $100<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- 20% off for orders over $200<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- Free shipping for orders over $50<br/>\n        4. Use switch statement for payment methods<br/>\n        5. Validate user input (positive numbers only)<br/><br/>\n        \n        <b>Implement with:</b><br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ if/else for discount logic<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ while loop for input validation<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ for loop to display cart items<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ switch for payment processing\n    </div>\n</div>"
            },
            "7-3": {
                "icon": "fa-shapes",
                "title": "Arrays, Objects & Functions",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 3: Arrays, Objects & Functions</h1>\n<p>Master data structures and functions - the core building blocks for organizing data and creating reusable code.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: Warehouse Organization üè≠</b><br/>\n    <ul style=\"margin-top: 10px;\">\n        <li><b>Arrays</b> = Shelves with numbered boxes</li>\n        <li><b>Objects</b> = Labeled storage containers</li>\n        <li><b>Functions</b> = Warehouse robots performing tasks</li>\n        <li><b>Parameters</b> = Instructions given to robots</li>\n        <li><b>Return values</b> = Products delivered by robots</li>\n    </ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Key Topics</h3>\n<ul>\n    <li>Arrays & Array Methods</li>\n    <li>Objects & Object Operations</li>\n    <li>Functions & Parameters</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Arrays: Ordered Collections</h3>\n\n<b>1. Creating and Accessing Arrays</b><br/>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Creating arrays<br/>\n        let fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"orange\"];<br/>\n        let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];<br/>\n        let mixed = [1, \"hello\", true, null];<br/><br/>\n        // Accessing elements (zero-indexed)<br/>\n        console.log(fruits[0]);&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"apple\"<br/>\n        console.log(fruits[1]);&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"banana\"<br/><br/>\n        // Modifying elements<br/>\n        fruits[1] = \"grape\";&nbsp;&nbsp;// Now [\"apple\", \"grape\", \"orange\"]\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>2. Common Array Methods</b>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;\">\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Method</th>\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Purpose</th>\n        <th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Example</th>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>push()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Add to end</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.push(\"item\")</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f9f9f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>pop()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Remove from end</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.pop()</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>shift()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Remove from start</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.shift()</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f9f9f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>unshift()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Add to start</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.unshift(\"item\")</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>slice()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Extract portion</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.slice(1, 3)</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background-color: #f9f9f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>splice()</pre></td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\">Add/remove elements</td>\n        <td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;\"><pre>arr.splice(1, 2)</pre></td>\n    </tr>\n</table>\n\n<b>3. Looping Through Arrays</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let colors = [\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\"];<br/><br/>\n        // For loop<br/>\n        for (let i = 0; i < colors.length; i++) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(colors[i]);<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // For...of loop (modern)<br/>\n        for (let color of colors) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(color);<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // forEach method<br/>\n        colors.forEach(function(color) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(color);<br/>\n        });\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Objects: Key-Value Collections</h3>\n\n<b>4. Creating and Accessing Objects</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Object literal<br/>\n        let person = {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;name: \"John\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 30,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;isStudent: true,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;hobbies: [\"reading\", \"gaming\"]<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        // Accessing properties<br/>\n        console.log(person.name);&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"John\"<br/>\n        console.log(person[\"age\"]);&nbsp;&nbsp;// 30 (bracket notation)<br/><br/>\n        // Adding/modifying properties<br/>\n        person.email = \"john@example.com\";<br/>\n        person.age = 31;\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>5. Object Methods & Nested Objects</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let car = {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;brand: \"Toyota\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;model: \"Camry\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;year: 2020,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Object method<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;startEngine: function() {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return \"Engine started!\";<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Nested object<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;specs: {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;color: \"blue\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;mpg: 32<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        console.log(car.startEngine());&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"Engine started!\"<br/>\n        console.log(car.specs.color);&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"blue\"\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>6. Looping Through Objects</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        let user = {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;name: \"Alice\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 25,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;role: \"Developer\"<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        // For...in loop<br/>\n        for (let key in user) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(key + \": \" + user[key]);<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // Object.keys()<br/>\n        let keys = Object.keys(user);&nbsp;&nbsp;// [\"name\", \"age\", \"role\"]<br/><br/>\n        // Object.values()<br/>\n        let values = Object.values(user);&nbsp;&nbsp;// [\"Alice\", 25, \"Developer\"]\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Functions: Reusable Code Blocks</h3>\n\n<b>7. Function Declaration & Calling</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Function declaration<br/>\n        function greet(name) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return \"Hello, \" + name + \"!\";<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // Calling the function<br/>\n        let message = greet(\"Sarah\");<br/>\n        console.log(message);&nbsp;&nbsp;// \"Hello, Sarah!\"<br/><br/>\n        // Multiple parameters<br/>\n        function calculateArea(length, width) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return length * width;<br/>\n        }<br/>\n        let area = calculateArea(5, 3);&nbsp;&nbsp;// 15\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>8. Function Expressions & Arrow Functions</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Function expression<br/>\n        const multiply = function(a, b) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return a * b;<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        // Arrow function (modern)<br/>\n        const divide = (a, b) => {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return a / b;<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        // Arrow function - one line<br/>\n        const square = x => x * x;<br/><br/>\n        // Arrow function - no parameters<br/>\n        const sayHello = () => \"Hello!\";\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>9. Default Parameters & Return Values</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Default parameters<br/>\n        function createUser(name, role = \"guest\") {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;username: name,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;userRole: role<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;};<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        let user1 = createUser(\"Bob\");&nbsp;&nbsp;// role = \"guest\"<br/>\n        let user2 = createUser(\"Alice\", \"admin\");<br/><br/>\n        // Functions returning arrays/objects<br/>\n        function getStats() {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;hp: 100,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;mp: 50,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;level: 5<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;};<br/>\n        }<br/>\n        let playerStats = getStats();\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Combining Concepts</h3>\n\n<b>Example 1: Shopping Cart System</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Array of product objects<br/>\n        let cart = [<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;{ name: \"Laptop\", price: 999, quantity: 1 },<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;{ name: \"Mouse\", price: 25, quantity: 2 }<br/>\n        ];<br/><br/>\n        // Function to calculate total<br/>\n        function calculateTotal(items) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;let total = 0;<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;for (let item of items) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;total += item.price * item.quantity;<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return total;<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        let cartTotal = calculateTotal(cart);<br/>\n        console.log(\"Total: $\" + cartTotal);\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>Example 2: Student Management</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // Object with array property<br/>\n        let classroom = {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;name: \"JavaScript 101\",<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;students: [\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Charlie\"],<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Method using array<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;addStudent: function(studentName) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;this.students.push(studentName);<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Method returning object<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;getReport: function() {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;className: this.name,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;studentCount: this.students.length,<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;students: this.students<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;};<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>\n        };<br/><br/>\n        classroom.addStudent(\"Diana\");<br/>\n        let report = classroom.getReport();\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Common Mistakes</h3>\n\n<b>Mistake 1: Modifying Arrays/Objects Incorrectly</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // WRONG - Trying to reassign entire array<br/>\n        let nums = [1, 2, 3];<br/>\n        nums = [4, 5, 6];&nbsp;&nbsp;// This works but might not be intended<br/><br/>\n        // BETTER - Modify existing array<br/>\n        nums.length = 0;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Clear array<br/>\n        nums.push(4, 5, 6);&nbsp;&nbsp;// Add new items\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<b>Mistake 2: Forgetting Return Statement</b>\n<div style=\"background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n    <pre>\n        // WRONG - No return value<br/>\n        function add(a, b) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;let sum = a + b;<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;// Missing return!<br/>\n        }<br/><br/>\n        // RIGHT<br/>\n        function add(a, b) {<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;return a + b;<br/>\n        }\n    </pre>\n</div>\n\n<hr/>\n\n<div class=\"assignment-box\">\n    <h4>Assignment: Library Management System</h4>\n    <p>Create a library system using arrays, objects, and functions:</p>\n    \n    <div style=\"background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;\">\n        <b>Requirements:</b><br/>\n        1. Create book objects with properties:<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;title, author, isbn, available (boolean)<br/>\n        2. Store books in an array<br/>\n        3. Create functions for:<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- addBook(title, author, isbn)<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- borrowBook(isbn)<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- returnBook(isbn)<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- findBooksByAuthor(author)<br/>\n        &nbsp;&nbsp;- getAvailableBooks()<br/><br/>\n        \n        <b>Implement with:</b><br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ Objects for book structure<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ Array methods (push, find, filter)<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ Arrow functions for operations<br/>\n        ‚Ä¢ Loops for displaying books\n    </div>\n    \n    <p><b>Bonus Challenge:</b> Add a user system with borrowing history tracking.</p>\n</div>"
            },
            "7-4": {
                icon: "fab fa-js",
                title: "Arrays & Objects Basics",
                html: `<h1>Week 7, Day 4: Arrays & Objects Basics</h1>
    <p>Today we'll learn how to work with complex data structures - arrays and objects.</p>
    
    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Organizing Your Digital Life üìö</b><br/>
        
        <pre>Arrays</pre>: Like a numbered list or shopping list<br/>
        <pre>Objects</pre>: Like a contact card with different info fields<br/>
        <pre>Array Index</pre>: The position number in your list (starts at 0!)<br/>
        <pre>Object Properties</pre>: The labels on your contact card (name, phone, email)<br/>
        <pre>Array Methods</pre>: Tools to organize your list (sort, filter, search)<br/>
        <pre>JSON</pre>: A standard format for exchanging data between applications<br/>
        <pre>Destructuring</pre>: Unpacking a packed suitcase of data
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Creating and Accessing Arrays</li>
        <li>Common Array Methods</li>
        <li>Creating and Accessing Objects</li>
        <li>Object Methods and Properties</li>
        <li>Introduction to JSON</li>
        <li>Combining Arrays and Objects</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>In-Depth Explanation</h3>
    
    <b>a. Arrays: Ordered Collections</b><br/>
    
    <b>Creating Arrays:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            // Method 1: Array literal (recommended)<br/>
            let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];<br/>
            let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];<br/>
            let mixed = [1, "hello", true, null];<br/>
            <br/>
            // Method 2: Array constructor<br/>
            let colors = new Array("red", "green", "blue");<br/>
            <br/>
            // Empty arrays<br/>
            let emptyArray = [];<br/>
            let sizedArray = new Array(5); // Creates array with 5 empty slots<br/>
            <br/>
            // Arrays can hold any data type<br/>
            let complexArray = [<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"string",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;42,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;true,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;{ name: "John" },<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;[1, 2, 3],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;function() { console.log("hi"); }<br/>
            ];
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Accessing Array Elements:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange", "grape", "mango"];<br/>
            <br/>
            // Access by index (0-based)<br/>
            console.log(fruits[0]);    // "apple"<br/>
            console.log(fruits[2]);    // "orange"<br/>
            console.log(fruits[4]);    // "mango"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Last element<br/>
            console.log(fruits[fruits.length - 1]);  // "mango"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Modify elements<br/>
            fruits[1] = "blueberry";   // Changes "banana" to "blueberry"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Adding elements<br/>
            fruits[5] = "pineapple";   // Adds at index 5<br/>
            fruits.push("strawberry"); // Adds to end<br/>
            fruits.unshift("kiwi");    // Adds to beginning<br/>
            <br/>
            // Array length<br/>
            console.log(fruits.length); // 7<br/>
            <br/>
            // Iterating through array<br/>
            for (let i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\`Fruit \${i}: \${fruits[i]}\`);<br/>
            }
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Common Array Methods:</b>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background-color: #f0f0f0;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Method</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Purpose</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Example</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Returns</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">push()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Add to end</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.push("item")</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">New length</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">pop()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Remove from end</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.pop()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Removed item</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">shift()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Remove from start</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.shift()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Removed item</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">unshift()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Add to start</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.unshift("item")</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">New length</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">slice()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Copy portion</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.slice(1, 3)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">New array</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">splice()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Add/remove items</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.splice(1, 2)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Removed items</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">indexOf()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Find item index</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.indexOf("item")</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Index or -1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">includes()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Check if exists</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.includes("item")</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">true/false</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">join()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Convert to string</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.join(", ")</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">String</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">reverse()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reverse order</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.reverse()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reversed array</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">sort()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Sort elements</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">arr.sort()</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Sorted array</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    
    <b>Array Method Examples:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];<br/>
            <br/>
            // Adding/removing<br/>
            numbers.push(6);        // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]<br/>
            numbers.pop();          // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]<br/>
            numbers.unshift(0);     // [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]<br/>
            numbers.shift();        // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]<br/>
            <br/>
            // Slicing and splicing<br/>
            let slice1 = numbers.slice(1, 3);   // [2, 3] (original unchanged)<br/>
            numbers.splice(1, 2);               // [1, 4, 5] (removes 2, 3)<br/>
            numbers.splice(1, 0, 2, 3);         // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] (inserts)<br/>
            <br/>
            // Searching<br/>
            console.log(numbers.indexOf(3));    // 2<br/>
            console.log(numbers.includes(7));   // false<br/>
            <br/>
            // Transforming<br/>
            console.log(numbers.join(" - "));   // "1 - 2 - 3 - 4 - 5"<br/>
            numbers.reverse();                  // [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]<br/>
            numbers.sort();                     // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]<br/>
            <br/>
            // Iteration methods (more on these later)<br/>
            numbers.forEach(function(num) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(num * 2);<br/>
            });
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>b. Objects: Key-Value Collections</b><br/>
    
    <b>Creating Objects:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            // Method 1: Object literal (recommended)<br/>
            let person = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;firstName: "John",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;lastName: "Doe",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 30,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;isStudent: false,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;address: {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;street: "123 Main St",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;city: "New York"<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;hobbies: ["reading", "swimming", "coding"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;greet: function() {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return \`Hello, my name is \${this.firstName}\`;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>
            };<br/>
            <br/>
            // Method 2: Object constructor<br/>
            let car = new Object();<br/>
            car.make = "Toyota";<br/>
            car.model = "Camry";<br/>
            car.year = 2020;<br/>
            <br/>
            // Empty object<br/>
            let emptyObject = {};<br/>
            <br/>
            // Object with computed property names<br/>
            let key = "dynamicKey";<br/>
            let obj = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;[key]: "dynamic value",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;["computed" + "Key"]: "computed value"<br/>
            };
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Accessing Object Properties:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            let book = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;title: "The Great Gatsby",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;author: "F. Scott Fitzgerald",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;year: 1925,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"page-count": 218  // Property with special characters<br/>
            };<br/>
            <br/>
            // Dot notation (most common)<br/>
            console.log(book.title);      // "The Great Gatsby"<br/>
            console.log(book.author);     // "F. Scott Fitzgerald"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Bracket notation (useful for dynamic keys)<br/>
            console.log(book["title"]);   // "The Great Gatsby"<br/>
            console.log(book["page-count"]); // 218 (required for special chars)<br/>
            <br/>
            // Dynamic property access<br/>
            let propertyName = "author";<br/>
            console.log(book[propertyName]); // "F. Scott Fitzgerald"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Adding new properties<br/>
            book.genre = "Fiction";<br/>
            book["rating"] = 4.5;<br/>
            <br/>
            // Modifying properties<br/>
            book.year = 2023;  // Updates the year<br/>
            <br/>
            // Deleting properties<br/>
            delete book.rating;<br/>
            <br/>
            // Checking if property exists<br/>
            console.log("title" in book);        // true<br/>
            console.log(book.hasOwnProperty("title")); // true<br/>
            console.log(book.publisher);         // undefined<br/>
            <br/>
            // Calling object methods<br/>
            let calculator = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;add: function(a, b) { return a + b; },<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;multiply(a, b) { return a * b; }  // Shorthand method<br/>
            };<br/>
            console.log(calculator.add(5, 3));      // 8<br/>
            console.log(calculator.multiply(4, 2)); // 8
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Object Methods for Working with Properties:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            let user = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;name: "Alice",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 25,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;email: "alice@example.com"<br/>
            };<br/>
            <br/>
            // Get all keys<br/>
            let keys = Object.keys(user);<br/>
            console.log(keys); // ["name", "age", "email"]<br/>
            <br/>
            // Get all values<br/>
            let values = Object.values(user);<br/>
            console.log(values); // ["Alice", 25, "alice@example.com"]<br/>
            <br/>
            // Get key-value pairs<br/>
            let entries = Object.entries(user);<br/>
            console.log(entries); // [["name", "Alice"], ["age", 25], ["email", "alice@example.com"]]<br/>
            <br/>
            // Loop through object<br/>
            for (let key in user) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\`\${key}: \${user[key]}\`);<br/>
            }<br/>
            <br/>
            Object.keys(user).forEach(function(key) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;console.log(\`\${key}: \${user[key]}\`);<br/>
            });<br/>
            <br/>
            // Copy object (shallow copy)<br/>
            let userCopy = Object.assign({}, user);<br/>
            let userCopy2 = { ...user };  // Spread operator (ES6)<br/>
            <br/>
            // Freeze object (cannot modify)<br/>
            Object.freeze(user);<br/>
            user.age = 30;  // Won't work in strict mode<br/>
            <br/>
            // Check if frozen<br/>
            console.log(Object.isFrozen(user)); // true
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>c. Combining Arrays and Objects</b><br/>
    
    <b>Array of Objects (Very Common Pattern):</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            // Array of objects - like a database table<br/>
            let students = [<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;{<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;id: 1,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;name: "Alice Johnson",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;age: 20,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;courses: ["Math", "Physics", "Chemistry"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;grades: { math: 90, physics: 85, chemistry: 88 }<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;{<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;id: 2,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;name: "Bob Smith",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;age: 21,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;courses: ["Biology", "History"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;grades: { biology: 92, history: 78 }<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;{<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;id: 3,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;name: "Charlie Brown",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;age: 19,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;courses: ["Computer Science", "Math"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;grades: { cs: 95, math: 89 }<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>
            ];<br/>
            <br/>
            // Accessing data<br/>
            console.log(students[0].name);               // "Alice Johnson"<br/>
            console.log(students[1].courses[0]);         // "Biology"<br/>
            console.log(students[2].grades.cs);          // 95<br/>
            <br/>
            // Adding a new student<br/>
            students.push({<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;id: 4,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;name: "Diana Prince",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 22<br/>
            });<br/>
            <br/>
            // Finding a student by ID<br/>
            function findStudentById(id) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;return students.find(function(student) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return student.id === id;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;});<br/>
            }<br/>
            <br/>
            let student = findStudentById(2);<br/>
            console.log(student.name);  // "Bob Smith"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Calculating average age<br/>
            let totalAge = 0;<br/>
            students.forEach(function(student) {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;totalAge += student.age;<br/>
            });<br/>
            let averageAge = totalAge / students.length;<br/>
            console.log(\`Average age: \${averageAge}\`);
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>d. Introduction to JSON</b><br/>
    
    <b>What is JSON?</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        JSON = JavaScript Object Notation<br/>
        - Lightweight data interchange format<br/>
        - Easy for humans to read and write<br/>
        - Easy for machines to parse and generate<br/>
        - Based on JavaScript object syntax<br/>
        - Language independent (used by many programming languages)<br/>
        - Commonly used for APIs and configuration files
    </div>
    
    <b>JSON vs JavaScript Objects:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            // JavaScript object<br/>
            let person = {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;name: "John",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;age: 30,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;isStudent: false,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;hobbies: ["reading", "swimming"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;address: {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;city: "New York",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;country: "USA"<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;},<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;greet: function() {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return "Hello!";<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;}  // ‚ùå Functions not allowed in JSON!<br/>
            };<br/>
            <br/>
            // JSON string (notice: double quotes, no functions)<br/>
            let jsonString = '{<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"name": "John",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"age": 30,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"isStudent": false,<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"hobbies": ["reading", "swimming"],<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;"address": {<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"city": "New York",<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"country": "USA"<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br/>
            }';<br/>
            <br/>
            // Converting between JavaScript and JSON<br/>
            let obj = { name: "Alice", age: 25 };<br/>
            <br/>
            // Object to JSON string<br/>
            let json = JSON.stringify(obj);<br/>
            console.log(json); // '{"name":"Alice","age":25}'<br/>
            console.log(typeof json); // "string"<br/>
            <br/>
            // JSON string to object<br/>
            let parsedObj = JSON.parse(json);<br/>
            console.log(parsedObj.name); // "Alice"<br/>
            console.log(typeof parsedObj); // "object"<br/>
            <br/>
            // Pretty printing JSON<br/>
            let prettyJson = JSON.stringify(obj, null, 2);<br/>
            console.log(prettyJson);<br/>
            // {<br/>
            //   "name": "Alice",<br/>
            //   "age": 25<br/>
            // }
        </pre>
