            "11-2": {
                icon: "fa-search",
                title: "SQL Basics: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 2: SQL Basics - SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE</h1>
            <p>Today we dive into the four fundamental SQL operations: retrieving data (SELECT), adding data (INSERT), modifying data (UPDATE), and removing data (DELETE). These are the building blocks of all database interactions.</p>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <b>Analogy: The Library Catalog System üìö</b><br/>
                
                SELECT: Searching for books in the catalog<br/>
                INSERT: Adding new books to the library<br/>
                UPDATE: Updating book information or location<br/>
                DELETE: Removing damaged or lost books<br/>
                WHERE: Your search criteria (author, genre, year)<br/>
                ORDER BY: Sorting results (A-Z, newest first)<br/>
                LIMIT: Only showing top 10 results<br/>
                JOIN: Finding related books (same author, series)
            </div>

            <h3>The SELECT Statement - Retrieving Data</h3>

            <b>Basic SELECT Syntax:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Select all columns from a table
            SELECT * FROM users;

            -- 2. Select specific columns
            SELECT username, email, created_at FROM users;

            -- 3. Select with column aliases
            SELECT 
                username AS 'User Name',
                email AS 'Email Address',
                created_at AS 'Registration Date'
            FROM users;

            -- 4. Select distinct values (remove duplicates)
            SELECT DISTINCT type FROM transactions;

            -- 5. Select with calculated columns
            SELECT 
                description,
                amount,
                amount * 1.1 AS 'amount_with_tax'
            FROM transactions;

            -- 6. Select with string functions
            SELECT 
                UPPER(username) AS uppercase_name,
                LOWER(email) AS lowercase_email,
                CONCAT(full_name, ' (', username, ')') AS display_name
            FROM users;

            -- 7. Select with date functions
            SELECT 
                transaction_date,
                DAY(transaction_date) AS day_of_month,
                MONTHNAME(transaction_date) AS month_name,
                YEAR(transaction_date) AS year,
                DATE_FORMAT(transaction_date, '%M %d, %Y') AS formatted_date
            FROM transactions;
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Filtering Data with WHERE Clause</h3>

            <b>WHERE Clause Examples:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Basic equality
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE user_id = 1;
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE type = 'expense';

            -- 2. Comparison operators
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE amount > 100;
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE amount <= 50;
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE amount <> 0;  -- not equal

            -- 3. Multiple conditions with AND/OR
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE type = 'expense' AND amount > 50;

            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE type = 'income' OR amount > 200;

            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE (type = 'expense' AND amount > 100) 
            OR (type = 'income' AND amount < 500);

            -- 4. BETWEEN for ranges
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE amount BETWEEN 50 AND 200;

            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE transaction_date BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-01-31';

            -- 5. IN for multiple values
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE category_id IN (1, 2, 3);

            SELECT * FROM users 
            WHERE username IN ('john_doe', 'jane_smith');

            -- 6. LIKE for pattern matching
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE email LIKE '%@gmail.com';
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE description LIKE '%groceries%';
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE username LIKE 'j%';  -- starts with j
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE username LIKE '%_doe';  -- ends with _doe

            -- 7. NOT for negation
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE type NOT IN ('income');
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE username NOT LIKE '%test%';
            SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE amount NOT BETWEEN 10 AND 100;

            -- 8. NULL checks
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE full_name IS NULL;
            SELECT * FROM users WHERE full_name IS NOT NULL;

            -- 9. Complex conditions with parentheses
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE (type = 'expense' AND amount > 100)
            OR (type = 'income' AND amount < 300)
            OR (description LIKE '%important%');
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Sorting and Limiting Results</h3>

            <b>ORDER BY and LIMIT Examples:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Basic sorting
            SELECT * FROM transactions ORDER BY transaction_date;
            SELECT * FROM transactions ORDER BY amount DESC;

            -- 2. Multiple column sorting
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            ORDER BY type, amount DESC;

            SELECT * FROM users 
            ORDER BY created_at DESC, username ASC;

            -- 3. Limit results
            SELECT * FROM transactions LIMIT 10;
            SELECT * FROM transactions ORDER BY amount DESC LIMIT 5;

            -- 4. Pagination with OFFSET
            -- Page 1: Records 1-10
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            ORDER BY transaction_date DESC 
            LIMIT 10 OFFSET 0;

            -- Page 2: Records 11-20
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            ORDER BY transaction_date DESC 
            LIMIT 10 OFFSET 10;

            -- Page 3: Records 21-30
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            ORDER BY transaction_date DESC 
            LIMIT 10 OFFSET 20;

            -- 5. Top N per category
            SELECT * FROM (
                SELECT 
                    *,
                    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY type ORDER BY amount DESC) as row_num
                FROM transactions
            ) ranked
            WHERE row_num <= 3;

            -- 6. Random sampling
            SELECT * FROM transactions ORDER BY RAND() LIMIT 5;
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>The INSERT Statement - Adding Data</h3>

            <b>INSERT Statement Examples:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Insert single row with all columns (except auto-increment)
            INSERT INTO users (username, email, password_hash, full_name, monthly_budget)
            VALUES ('alice_wonder', 'alice@example.com', 'hashed_password123', 'Alice Wonder', 3200.00);

            -- 2. Insert single row with only required columns
            INSERT INTO users (username, email, password_hash)
            VALUES ('bob_builder', 'bob@builder.com', 'hashed_password456');

            -- 3. Insert multiple rows at once
            INSERT INTO categories (user_id, name, type, color) VALUES
            (1, 'Rent', 'expense', '#FF6B6B'),
            (1, 'Car Payment', 'expense', '#4ECDC4'),
            (1, 'Dividends', 'income', '#45B7D1'),
            (1, 'Rental Income', 'income', '#96CEB4');

            -- 4. Insert with subquery (copy data)
            INSERT INTO transactions_backup
            SELECT * FROM transactions 
            WHERE transaction_date < '2023-01-01';

            -- 5. Insert with default values
            INSERT INTO users (username, email, password_hash)
            VALUES ('charlie_brown', 'charlie@example.com', 'hashed_password789');

            -- 6. Insert ignoring duplicates
            INSERT IGNORE INTO users (username, email, password_hash)
            VALUES ('john_doe', 'john_new@example.com', 'hashed_password999');

            -- 7. Insert or update (UPSERT)
            INSERT INTO users (user_id, username, email, password_hash)
            VALUES (1, 'john_doe_updated', 'john_updated@example.com', 'new_hash')
            ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE 
                username = VALUES(username),
                email = VALUES(email),
                password_hash = VALUES(password_hash),
                updated_at = NOW();

            -- 8. Insert with CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
            INSERT INTO transactions (user_id, category_id, amount, type, description, transaction_date)
            VALUES (1, 1, 75.50, 'expense', 'Dinner with friends', CURDATE());

            -- 9. Insert with calculated values
            INSERT INTO savings_goals (user_id, goal_name, target_amount, current_amount)
            VALUES (1, 'New Phone', 1000.00, ROUND(RAND() * 500, 2));

            -- 10. Insert from another table with transformation
            INSERT INTO transaction_archive (user_id, amount, type, description, archived_date)
            SELECT 
                user_id,
                amount,
                type,
                CONCAT('ARCHIVED: ', description),
                NOW()
            FROM transactions 
            WHERE transaction_date < '2023-01-01';
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>The UPDATE Statement - Modifying Data</h3>

            <b>UPDATE Statement Examples:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ö†Ô∏è WARNING: Always use WHERE with UPDATE! ‚ö†Ô∏è
            -- Without WHERE, you update ALL rows in the table!

            -- 1. Update single row
            UPDATE users 
            SET full_name = 'Johnathan Doe'
            WHERE user_id = 1;

            -- 2. Update multiple columns
            UPDATE users 
            SET 
                monthly_budget = 4000.00,
                currency = 'EUR',
                updated_at = NOW()
            WHERE user_id = 1;

            -- 3. Update with calculation
            UPDATE transactions 
            SET amount = amount * 1.05  -- Increase all by 5%
            WHERE type = 'expense' 
            AND transaction_date >= '2024-01-01';

            -- 4. Update with subquery
            UPDATE savings_goals 
            SET current_amount = (
                SELECT SUM(amount) 
                FROM transactions 
                WHERE type = 'income' 
                AND user_id = savings_goals.user_id
                )
            WHERE user_id = 1;

            -- 5. Update with CASE statement (conditional update)
            UPDATE transactions 
            SET description = CASE
                WHEN amount > 500 THEN CONCAT('LARGE: ', description)
                WHEN amount < 10 THEN CONCAT('SMALL: ', description)
                ELSE description
            END
            WHERE transaction_date >= '2024-01-01';

            -- 6. Update based on another table
            UPDATE users u
            JOIN (
                SELECT user_id, SUM(amount) as total_income
                FROM transactions 
                WHERE type = 'income'
                GROUP BY user_id
            ) t ON u.user_id = t.user_id
            SET u.monthly_budget = t.total_income * 0.8  -- Set budget to 80% of income
            WHERE u.user_id = 1;

            -- 7. Update with LIMIT (safe for large tables)
            UPDATE transactions 
            SET category_id = 5  -- Uncategorized
            WHERE category_id IS NULL
            LIMIT 100;  -- Update 100 rows at a time

            -- 8. Increment/Decrement values
            UPDATE savings_goals 
            SET current_amount = current_amount + 100
            WHERE goal_id = 1;

            UPDATE product_inventory 
            SET quantity = quantity - 1
            WHERE product_id = 5 AND quantity > 0;

            -- 9. Update with JSON functions (MySQL 5.7+)
            UPDATE users 
            SET preferences = JSON_SET(
                COALESCE(preferences, '{}'),
                '$.theme', 'dark',
                '$.notifications', true
            )
            WHERE user_id = 1;

            -- 10. Update timestamp only if changed
            UPDATE users 
            SET 
                full_name = 'New Name',
                updated_at = CASE 
                    WHEN full_name <> 'New Name' THEN NOW()
                    ELSE updated_at
                END
            WHERE user_id = 1;
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>The DELETE Statement - Removing Data</h3>

            <b>DELETE Statement Examples:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ö†Ô∏è DOUBLE WARNING: Always use WHERE with DELETE! ‚ö†Ô∏è
            -- Without WHERE, you delete ALL rows in the table!

            -- 1. Delete single row
            DELETE FROM users WHERE user_id = 999;

            -- 2. Delete multiple rows with condition
            DELETE FROM transactions 
            WHERE transaction_date < '2023-01-01';

            -- 3. Delete with LIMIT (safe deletion)
            DELETE FROM error_logs 
            WHERE created_at < '2023-06-01'
            LIMIT 1000;  -- Delete 1000 rows at a time

            -- 4. Delete duplicate rows (keep one)
            DELETE t1 FROM transactions t1
            INNER JOIN transactions t2 
            WHERE 
                t1.transaction_id < t2.transaction_id  -- Keep higher ID
                AND t1.user_id = t2.user_id
                AND t1.amount = t2.amount
                AND t1.type = t2.type
                AND DATE(t1.transaction_date) = DATE(t2.transaction_date);

            -- 5. Delete with subquery
            DELETE FROM transactions 
            WHERE category_id IN (
                SELECT category_id 
                FROM categories 
                WHERE name = 'Obsolete Category'
            );

            -- 6. Delete orphaned records (no foreign key reference)
            DELETE FROM categories 
            WHERE user_id NOT IN (
                SELECT user_id FROM users
            );

            -- 7. Delete with JOIN
            DELETE t
            FROM transactions t
            LEFT JOIN categories c ON t.category_id = c.category_id
            WHERE c.category_id IS NULL;  -- Delete transactions with non-existent categories

            -- 8. Delete all data from table (truncate is faster)
            TRUNCATE TABLE temp_data;  -- Cannot be rolled back!

            -- 9. Delete with ORDER BY (delete oldest first)
            DELETE FROM session_logs 
            ORDER BY created_at ASC
            LIMIT 1000;

            -- 10. Soft delete (mark as deleted instead of removing)
            UPDATE transactions 
            SET is_deleted = 1, deleted_at = NOW()
            WHERE transaction_date < '2023-01-01';
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Practical Examples for Finance App</h3>

            <b>Real-World SQL Queries for Our Application:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Get user's monthly summary
            SELECT 
                u.username,
                u.monthly_budget,
                COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN t.type = 'income' THEN t.amount ELSE 0 END), 0) AS total_income,
                COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN t.type = 'expense' THEN t.amount ELSE 0 END), 0) AS total_expenses,
                COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN t.type = 'income' THEN t.amount ELSE -t.amount END), 0) AS net_balance,
                u.monthly_budget - COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN t.type = 'expense' THEN t.amount ELSE 0 END), 0) AS budget_remaining
            FROM users u
            LEFT JOIN transactions t ON u.user_id = t.user_id 
                AND MONTH(t.transaction_date) = MONTH(CURRENT_DATE())
                AND YEAR(t.transaction_date) = YEAR(CURRENT_DATE())
            WHERE u.user_id = 1
            GROUP BY u.user_id;

            -- 2. Get category-wise spending for current month
            SELECT 
                c.name AS category_name,
                c.color,
                COUNT(t.transaction_id) AS transaction_count,
                SUM(t.amount) AS total_spent,
                AVG(t.amount) AS average_transaction,
                MAX(t.amount) AS largest_transaction,
                MIN(t.amount) AS smallest_transaction
            FROM categories c
            LEFT JOIN transactions t ON c.category_id = t.category_id 
                AND t.type = 'expense'
                AND MONTH(t.transaction_date) = MONTH(CURRENT_DATE())
                AND YEAR(t.transaction_date) = YEAR(CURRENT_DATE())
            WHERE c.user_id = 1 AND c.type = 'expense'
            GROUP BY c.category_id
            ORDER BY total_spent DESC;

            -- 3. Find recurring expenses (similar descriptions/amounts)
            SELECT 
                description,
                AVG(amount) AS average_amount,
                COUNT(*) AS occurrence_count,
                MIN(transaction_date) AS first_occurrence,
                MAX(transaction_date) AS last_occurrence,
                DATEDIFF(MAX(transaction_date), MIN(transaction_date)) / (COUNT(*) - 1) AS avg_days_between
            FROM transactions 
            WHERE user_id = 1 
                AND type = 'expense'
                AND transaction_date >= DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE(), INTERVAL 6 MONTH)
            GROUP BY description, ROUND(amount, -1)  -- Group similar amounts
            HAVING COUNT(*) >= 3  -- At least 3 occurrences
            ORDER BY occurrence_count DESC;

            -- 4. Update savings goals based on transactions
            UPDATE savings_goals sg
            SET current_amount = (
                SELECT COALESCE(SUM(amount), 0)
                FROM transactions t
                WHERE t.user_id = sg.user_id
                    AND t.type = 'income'
                    AND t.transaction_date >= DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE(), INTERVAL 30 DAY)
            ),
            updated_at = NOW()
            WHERE sg.user_id = 1;

            -- 5. Clean up old temporary data
            DELETE FROM temp_sessions 
            WHERE created_at < DATE_SUB(NOW(), INTERVAL 24 HOUR);

            -- 6. Insert monthly budget from template
            INSERT INTO budgets (user_id, category_id, month_year, amount)
            SELECT 
                user_id,
                category_id,
                DATE_FORMAT(CURRENT_DATE(), '%Y-%m-01'),
                amount * 1.03  -- Increase by 3% from last month
            FROM budgets 
            WHERE month_year = DATE_FORMAT(DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE(), INTERVAL 1 MONTH), '%Y-%m-01')
            ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE amount = VALUES(amount);

            -- 7. Find users with unusual spending patterns
            SELECT 
                u.user_id,
                u.username,
                AVG(t.amount) AS avg_daily_spending,
                STD(t.amount) AS spending_volatility,
                COUNT(DISTINCT DATE(t.transaction_date)) AS active_days,
                SUM(t.amount) / DATEDIFF(MAX(t.transaction_date), MIN(t.transaction_date)) AS avg_daily_over_period
            FROM users u
            JOIN transactions t ON u.user_id = t.user_id 
                AND t.type = 'expense'
                AND t.transaction_date >= DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE(), INTERVAL 30 DAY)
            GROUP BY u.user_id
            HAVING avg_daily_spending > (u.monthly_budget / 30) * 1.5  -- 50% over budget
            ORDER BY avg_daily_spending DESC;
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Today's Hands-On Exercise</h3>

            <b>Task:</b> Practice all four SQL operations with our finance database.<br/><br/>

            <b>Step-by-Step Implementation:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                1. <b>SELECT Practice (30 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Retrieve all users with their registration dates</li>
                    <li>Find transactions over $100 from January 2024</li>
