            "11-3": {
                icon: "fa-sitemap",
                title: "Database Normalization & Primary Keys",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 3: Database Normalization & Primary Keys</h1>
            <p>Today we dive deep into database design principles. We'll learn how to structure databases efficiently through normalization and understand the critical role of primary keys in maintaining data integrity.</p>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <b>Analogy: The Organized Library vs. The Pile of Books üìö</b><br/>
                
                Unnormalized Data: All books thrown in one giant pile<br/>
                1st Normal Form (1NF): Books sorted by title on shelves<br/>
                2nd Normal Form (2NF): Separate sections for fiction/non-fiction<br/>
                3rd Normal Form (3NF): Alphabetical within genres, author indexes<br/>
                Primary Key: Unique library ID on each book's spine<br/>
                Foreign Key: Reference card pointing to related books<br/>
                Normalization: The process of organizing the library<br/>
                Denormalization: Creating themed display tables for quick browsing
            </div>

            <h3>The Need for Normalization</h3>

            <b>Problems with Poor Database Design:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ùå BAD DESIGN: Single table with everything (Flat Table)
            CREATE TABLE bad_design (
                order_id INT,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),
                customer_email VARCHAR(100),
                customer_phone VARCHAR(20),
                product_name VARCHAR(100),
                product_category VARCHAR(50),
                product_price DECIMAL(10,2),
                order_date DATE,
                quantity INT,
                total_price DECIMAL(10,2),
                shipping_address VARCHAR(255),
                billing_address VARCHAR(255)
            );

            -- Problems with this design:
            -- 1. Data Redundancy: Customer info repeated for every order
            -- 2. Update Anomalies: Changing customer email requires updating multiple rows
            -- 3. Insert Anomalies: Can't add a customer without an order
            -- 4. Delete Anomalies: Deleting last order deletes customer info
            -- 5. Inconsistent Data: Same customer might have different info in different rows
            -- 6. Wasted Storage: Repeated information takes up unnecessary space
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>First Normal Form (1NF)</h3>

            <b>Rules for 1NF:</b>
            <ol>
                <li>Each table cell should contain a single value (atomic values)</li>
                <li>Each record needs to be unique (no duplicate rows)</li>
                <li>Columns should contain values of the same type</li>
            </ol>

            <b>Example: Transforming to 1NF</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ùå BEFORE 1NF: Violates atomicity
            CREATE TABLE unnormalized_orders (
                order_id INT,
                customer_id INT,
                products VARCHAR(500)  -- Contains "Product A, Product B, Product C"
            );

            -- ‚úÖ AFTER 1NF: Atomic values
            CREATE TABLE orders_1nf (
                order_id INT,
                customer_id INT,
                product_id INT,  -- Single value per row
                quantity INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)  -- Composite key for uniqueness
            );

            -- Sample data showing the difference:
            -- ‚ùå Bad: Single row with comma-separated products
            -- order_id | customer_id | products
            -- 1        | 101         | "Laptop, Mouse, Keyboard"

            -- ‚úÖ Good: Multiple rows, one product per row
            -- order_id | customer_id | product_id | quantity
            -- 1        | 101         | 1          | 1
            -- 1        | 101         | 2          | 1
            -- 1        | 101         | 3          | 1
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Second Normal Form (2NF)</h3>

            <b>Rules for 2NF:</b>
            <ol>
                <li>Must already be in 1NF</li>
                <li>All non-key attributes must depend on the entire primary key</li>
                <li>No partial dependencies (attributes depending on only part of a composite key)</li>
            </ol>

            <b>Example: Transforming to 2NF</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ùå BEFORE 2NF: Contains partial dependencies
            CREATE TABLE orders_1nf_but_not_2nf (
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),  -- Depends only on order_id, not product_id
                product_name VARCHAR(100),   -- Depends only on product_id, not order_id
                quantity INT,
                order_date DATE,             -- Depends only on order_id
                product_price DECIMAL(10,2), -- Depends only on product_id
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)
            );

            -- ‚úÖ AFTER 2NF: Separate tables for different entities
            CREATE TABLE orders_2nf (
                order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_id INT,
                order_date DATE,
                FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)
            );

            CREATE TABLE order_items_2nf (
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                quantity INT,
                price_at_time DECIMAL(10,2),  -- Price when ordered (may differ from current)
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (order_id) REFERENCES orders_2nf(order_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)
            );

            CREATE TABLE customers_2nf (
                customer_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),
                email VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE products_2nf (
                product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                product_name VARCHAR(100),
                current_price DECIMAL(10,2)
            );
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Third Normal Form (3NF)</h3>

            <b>Rules for 3NF:</b>
            <ol>
                <li>Must already be in 2NF</li>
                <li>No transitive dependencies (non-key attributes depending on other non-key attributes)</li>
                <li>All attributes must depend only on the primary key</li>
            </ol>

            <b>Example: Transforming to 3NF</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ùå BEFORE 3NF: Contains transitive dependencies
            CREATE TABLE employees_2nf_but_not_3nf (
                employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                employee_name VARCHAR(100),
                department_id INT,
                department_name VARCHAR(100),  -- Depends on department_id, not employee_id
                department_location VARCHAR(100),  -- Also depends on department_id
                manager_id INT,
                manager_name VARCHAR(100)     -- Depends on manager_id, not employee_id
            );

            -- ‚úÖ AFTER 3NF: Remove transitive dependencies
            CREATE TABLE employees_3nf (
                employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                employee_name VARCHAR(100),
                department_id INT,
                manager_id INT,
                FOREIGN KEY (department_id) REFERENCES departments(department_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (manager_id) REFERENCES employees(employee_id)
            );

            CREATE TABLE departments_3nf (
                department_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                department_name VARCHAR(100),
                department_location VARCHAR(100)
            );

            -- Now:
            -- employee_name depends on employee_id (primary key) ‚úì
            -- department_id depends on employee_id (foreign key) ‚úì
            -- department_name depends on department_id (in separate table) ‚úì
            -- No transitive dependencies! ‚úì
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Boyce-Codd Normal Form (BCNF)</h3>

            <b>Advanced Normalization (Optional but Important):</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- BCNF deals with overlapping candidate keys
            -- A table is in BCNF if for every non-trivial functional dependency X ‚Üí Y, X is a superkey

            -- ‚ùå Example violating BCNF:
            -- Consider a university where:
            -- 1. Each student can have multiple advisors
            -- 2. Each advisor advises in only one department
            -- 3. Each student can be in only one department

            CREATE TABLE student_advising (
                student_id INT,
                advisor_id INT,
                department VARCHAR(100),
                PRIMARY KEY (student_id, advisor_id)
            );

            -- Functional dependencies:
            -- 1. advisor_id ‚Üí department (Each advisor belongs to one department)
            -- 2. student_id ‚Üí department (Each student is in one department)
            -- Problem: advisor_id is not a superkey but determines department

            -- ‚úÖ BCNF Solution: Split the table
            CREATE TABLE students (
                student_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                department VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE advisors (
                advisor_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                department VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE student_advisor (
                student_id INT,
                advisor_id INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (student_id, advisor_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(student_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (advisor_id) REFERENCES advisors(advisor_id)
            );
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Primary Keys: The Foundation of Data Integrity</h3>

            <b>Types of Primary Keys:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. Natural Key (Business Key)
            CREATE TABLE employees_natural (
                employee_code VARCHAR(20) PRIMARY KEY,  -- e.g., "EMP-001"
                name VARCHAR(100),
                department VARCHAR(50)
            );
            -- Pros: Meaningful, no extra column needed
            -- Cons: May change (business rules), longer, slower joins

            -- 2. Surrogate Key (Technical Key)
            CREATE TABLE employees_surrogate (
                employee_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,  -- System-generated
                employee_code VARCHAR(20) UNIQUE,  -- Still have business key
                name VARCHAR(100),
                department VARCHAR(50)
            );
            -- Pros: Never changes, shorter, faster joins
            -- Cons: Not meaningful, requires extra column

            -- 3. Composite Key (Multiple Columns)
            CREATE TABLE order_items_composite (
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                quantity INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)  -- Both columns together form the key
            );
            -- Pros: Represents natural relationships, prevents duplicates
            -- Cons: More complex, slower joins with multiple columns

            -- 4. GUID/UUID Key (Global Unique Identifier)
            CREATE TABLE users_uuid (
                user_id CHAR(36) PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT (UUID()),  -- e.g., "123e4567-e89b-12d3-a456-426614174000"
                username VARCHAR(50),
                email VARCHAR(100)
            );
            -- Pros: Globally unique, can generate offline
            -- Cons: Larger storage (36 chars), not sequential, slower indexes

            -- 5. Natural Composite Key
            CREATE TABLE city_natural_composite (
                country_code CHAR(2),
                city_name VARCHAR(100),
                population INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (country_code, city_name)  -- Naturally unique combination
            );
            -- Example: ("US", "Springfield") vs ("IL", "Springfield")
            </pre>
            </div>

            <b>Choosing the Right Primary Key Strategy:</b>
            <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
            <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                <thead>
                    <tr style="background-color: #4A90E2; color: white;">
                        <th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Key Type</th>
                        <th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Best For</th>
                        <th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">When to Use</th>
                        <th style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">When to Avoid</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Auto-increment INT</b></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Most tables</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Default choice, simple tables</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Distributed systems, offline sync</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Natural Key</b></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reference data</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Countries, currencies, status codes</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">User data, changing business rules</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Composite Key</b></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Junction tables</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Many-to-many relationships</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Frequently joined tables</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>UUID</b></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Distributed systems</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Microservices, mobile apps, replication</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Small tables, performance-critical</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Custom Sequence</b></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Business documents</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Invoices, orders, tickets</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Generic data tables</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
            </div>

            <h3>Foreign Keys & Referential Integrity</h3>

            <b>Understanding Foreign Key Constraints:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- Basic foreign key
            CREATE TABLE orders (
                order_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_id INT,
                order_date DATE,
                FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id)
            );

            -- Foreign key with constraint naming
            CREATE TABLE order_items (
                order_item_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                quantity INT,
                CONSTRAINT fk_order_items_orders 
                    FOREIGN KEY (order_id) REFERENCES orders(order_id),
                CONSTRAINT fk_order_items_products
                    FOREIGN KEY (product_id) REFERENCES products(product_id)
            );

            -- ON DELETE actions
            CREATE TABLE child_table (
                id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                parent_id INT,
                FOREIGN KEY (parent_id) REFERENCES parent_table(parent_id)
                    ON DELETE CASCADE       -- Delete child when parent is deleted
                    -- ON DELETE SET NULL   -- Set child column to NULL
                    -- ON DELETE RESTRICT   -- Prevent parent deletion if children exist
                    -- ON DELETE NO ACTION  -- Same as RESTRICT but checked later
            );

            -- ON UPDATE actions
            CREATE TABLE child_table2 (
                id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                parent_id INT,
                FOREIGN KEY (parent_id) REFERENCES parent_table(parent_id)
                    ON UPDATE CASCADE       -- Update child when parent key changes
                    -- ON UPDATE SET NULL
                    -- ON UPDATE RESTRICT
            );

            -- Self-referencing foreign key (hierarchical data)
            CREATE TABLE employees (
                employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                name VARCHAR(100),
                manager_id INT,
                FOREIGN KEY (manager_id) REFERENCES employees(employee_id)
            );

            -- Composite foreign key
            CREATE TABLE order_details (
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                warehouse_id INT,
                quantity INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id, warehouse_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (order_id, product_id) 
                    REFERENCES order_items(order_id, product_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (warehouse_id) REFERENCES warehouses(warehouse_id)
            );
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Database Relationships</h3>

            <b>Types of Relationships and Their Implementation:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- 1. One-to-One Relationship
            -- Example: User and UserProfile (each user has one profile)
            CREATE TABLE users_one_to_one (
                user_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                username VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE
            );

            CREATE TABLE user_profiles (
                profile_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                user_id INT UNIQUE,  -- UNIQUE ensures one-to-one
                full_name VARCHAR(100),
                date_of_birth DATE,
                FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users_one_to_one(user_id)
            );

            -- 2. One-to-Many Relationship (Most Common)
            -- Example: Department and Employees (one department, many employees)
            CREATE TABLE departments_one_to_many (
                dept_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                dept_name VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE employees_one_to_many (
                emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                emp_name VARCHAR(100),
                dept_id INT,  -- Foreign key in the "many" side
                FOREIGN KEY (dept_id) REFERENCES departments_one_to_many(dept_id)
            );

            -- 3. Many-to-Many Relationship (Requires Junction Table)
            -- Example: Students and Courses (many students, many courses)
            CREATE TABLE students_many_to_many (
                student_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                student_name VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE courses_many_to_many (
                course_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                course_name VARCHAR(100)
            );

            -- Junction Table (Bridge Table)
            CREATE TABLE student_courses (
                student_id INT,
                course_id INT,
                enrollment_date DATE,
                grade CHAR(2),
                PRIMARY KEY (student_id, course_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students_many_to_many(student_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES courses_many_to_many(course_id)
            );

            -- 4. Hierarchical Relationship (Self-Referencing)
            -- Example: Employee organizational chart
            CREATE TABLE employees_hierarchical (
                employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                employee_name VARCHAR(100),
                manager_id INT,
                FOREIGN KEY (manager_id) REFERENCES employees_hierarchical(employee_id)
            );

            -- 5. Recursive Relationship with Additional Data
            -- Example: Bill of Materials (BOM)
            CREATE TABLE products_bom (
                product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                product_name VARCHAR(100)
            );

            CREATE TABLE bom_components (
                parent_product_id INT,
                child_product_id INT,
                quantity_required INT,
                PRIMARY KEY (parent_product_id, child_product_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (parent_product_id) REFERENCES products_bom(product_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (child_product_id) REFERENCES products_bom(product_id),
                CHECK (parent_product_id <> child_product_id)  -- Prevent self-reference
            );
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Practical Normalization Exercise</h3>

            <b>Normalizing a Real-World Example: E-commerce System</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- ‚ùå START: Completely unnormalized e-commerce data
            CREATE TABLE messy_orders (
                order_id INT,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),
                customer_email VARCHAR(100),
                customer_phone VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_address TEXT,
                billing_address TEXT,
                product_list TEXT,  -- "Product A:2, Product B:1, Product C:3"
                order_date DATE,
                total_amount DECIMAL(10,2),
                payment_method VARCHAR(50),
                payment_status VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_method VARCHAR(50),
                shipping_status VARCHAR(20)
            );

            -- ‚úÖ STEP 1: Apply 1NF (Atomic values, no repeating groups)
            CREATE TABLE orders_1nf (
                order_id INT,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),
                customer_email VARCHAR(100),
                customer_phone VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_address TEXT,
                billing_address TEXT,
                product_id INT,
                product_name VARCHAR(100),
                product_price DECIMAL(10,2),
                quantity INT,
                order_date DATE,
                payment_method VARCHAR(50),
                payment_status VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_method VARCHAR(50),
                shipping_status VARCHAR(20),
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id)
            );

            -- ‚úÖ STEP 2: Apply 2NF (Remove partial dependencies)
            -- Separate orders from order items
            CREATE TABLE orders_2nf (
                order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_id INT,
                order_date DATE,
                total_amount DECIMAL(10,2),
                payment_method VARCHAR(50),
                payment_status VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_method VARCHAR(50),
                shipping_status VARCHAR(20),
                shipping_address_id INT,
                billing_address_id INT
            );

            CREATE TABLE order_items_2nf (
                order_id INT,
                product_id INT,
                quantity INT,
                unit_price DECIMAL(10,2),
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, product_id),
                FOREIGN KEY (order_id) REFERENCES orders_2nf(order_id)
            );

            -- ‚úÖ STEP 3: Apply 3NF (Remove transitive dependencies)
            CREATE TABLE customers_3nf (
                customer_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),
                email VARCHAR(100),
                phone VARCHAR(20)
            );

            CREATE TABLE addresses_3nf (
                address_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_id INT,
                address_type ENUM('shipping', 'billing'),
                street_address VARCHAR(255),
                city VARCHAR(100),
                state VARCHAR(50),
                zip_code VARCHAR(20),
                country VARCHAR(50),
                FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers_3nf(customer_id)
            );

            CREATE TABLE products_3nf (
                product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                product_name VARCHAR(100),
                current_price DECIMAL(10,2),
                category_id INT,
                supplier_id INT
            );

            -- Final normalized schema:
            -- customers (customer_id, name, email, phone)
            -- addresses (address_id, customer_id, type, street, city, state, zip, country)
            -- orders (order_id, customer_id, order_date, total_amount, payment_method, 
            --         payment_status, shipping_method, shipping_status, shipping_address_id, billing_address_id)
            -- order_items (order_id, product_id, quantity, unit_price)
            -- products (product_id, product_name, current_price, category_id, supplier_id)
            -- categories (category_id, category_name)
            -- suppliers (supplier_id, supplier_name)
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>When to Denormalize</h3>

            <b>Strategic Denormalization for Performance:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <pre>
            -- Sometimes normalization hurts performance. Strategic denormalization can help:

            -- 1. Calculated Columns (Store pre-calculated values)
            CREATE TABLE orders_denormalized (
                order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                customer_id INT,
                order_date DATE,
                total_items INT,  -- Denormalized: Could calculate from order_items
                total_amount DECIMAL(10,2),  -- Denormalized: Could calculate sum
                last_updated TIMESTAMP,
                INDEX idx_customer_date (customer_id, order_date)
            );

            -- Update trigger to maintain denormalized data
            CREATE TRIGGER update_order_totals
            AFTER INSERT ON order_items
            FOR EACH ROW
            BEGIN
                UPDATE orders_denormalized 
                SET total_items = total_items + NEW.quantity,
                    total_amount = total_amount + (NEW.quantity * NEW.unit_price),
                    last_updated = NOW()
                WHERE order_id = NEW.order_id;
            END;

            -- 2. Flattened Hierarchies (For frequent queries)
            CREATE TABLE employee_flat (
                employee_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                employee_name VARCHAR(100),
                department_id INT,
                department_name VARCHAR(100),  -- Denormalized from departments table
                manager_id INT,
                manager_name VARCHAR(100),     -- Denormalized from employees table
                INDEX idx_department (department_id, department_name)
            );

            -- 3. Materialized Views (Pre-computed aggregations)
            CREATE TABLE daily_sales_summary (
                sale_date DATE PRIMARY KEY,
                total_orders INT,
                total_revenue DECIMAL(10,2),
                average_order_value DECIMAL(10,2),
                unique_customers INT,
                last_updated TIMESTAMP
            );

            -- Scheduled job to refresh:
            -- INSERT INTO daily_sales_summary 
            -- SELECT order_date, COUNT(*), SUM(total_amount), AVG(total_amount), 
            --        COUNT(DISTINCT customer_id), NOW()
            -- FROM orders 
            -- WHERE order_date = CURDATE() - INTERVAL 1 DAY
            -- ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE ...;

            -- 4. Archive Tables (Historical reporting)
            CREATE TABLE order_archive (
                order_id INT,
                customer_name VARCHAR(100),  -- Denormalized: Customer might be deleted
                product_names TEXT,          -- Denormalized: Products might change
                order_total DECIMAL(10,2),
                order_date DATE,
                archive_date TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
                PRIMARY KEY (order_id, archive_date)
            );

            -- Rules for Denormalization:
            -- 1. Only denormalize for proven performance issues
            -- 2. Document all denormalized fields
            -- 3. Implement triggers or jobs to maintain consistency
            -- 4. Test both read and write performance
            -- 5. Consider using views or materialized views first
            </pre>
            </div>

            <h3>Today's Hands-On Exercise</h3>

            <b>Task:</b> Design and normalize a complete database schema for a project management application.<br/><br/>

            <b>Step-by-Step Implementation:</b>
            <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                1. <b>Requirements Analysis (15 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Project management system for teams</li>
                    <li>Users can be in multiple teams</li>
                    <li>Each team has multiple projects</li>
                    <li>Each project has multiple tasks</li>
                    <li>Tasks can have subtasks</li>
                    <li>Users can be assigned to multiple tasks</li>
                    <li>Tasks have status, priority, due dates</li>
                    <li>Time tracking for tasks</li>
                    <li>File attachments for tasks</li>
                    <li>Comments/discussions on tasks</li>
                </ul>

                2. <b>Identify Entities (15 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>List all entities (nouns from requirements)</li>
                    <li>Identify attributes for each entity</li>
                    <li>Determine relationships between entities</li>
                    <li>Draw initial ERD on paper/whiteboard</li>
                </ul>

                3. <b>Create Unnormalized Schema (20 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Create one big table with everything</li>
                    <li>Identify all the normalization problems</li>
                    <li>List data redundancies and anomalies</li>
                    <li>Write the problematic CREATE TABLE statement</li>
                </ul>

                4. <b>Apply 1NF (20 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Ensure atomic values in each cell</li>
                    <li>Remove repeating groups</li>
                    <li>Create separate tables for multi-valued attributes</li>
                    <li>Define primary keys</li>
                </ul>

                5. <b>Apply 2NF (20 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify partial dependencies</li>
                    <li>Separate tables based on dependency</li>
                    <li>Create foreign key relationships</li>
                    <li>Ensure all non-key attributes depend on entire primary key</li>
                </ul>

                6. <b>Apply 3NF (20 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify transitive dependencies</li>
                    <li>Create additional tables as needed</li>
                    <li>Ensure all attributes depend only on the primary key</li>
                    <li>Review all relationships</li>
                </ul>

                7. <b>Implement in SQL (30 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Write complete CREATE TABLE statements</li>
                    <li>Define all primary and foreign keys</li>
                    <li>Add appropriate indexes</li>
                    <li>Insert sample data</li>
                </ul>

                8. <b>Test and Validate (20 minutes):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Test INSERT operations</li>
                    <li>Test UPDATE operations</li>
                    <li>Test DELETE operations</li>
                    <li>Verify referential integrity</li>
                    <li>Check for any remaining anomalies</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h3>Homework Assignment: Advanced Normalization</h3>

            <div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                <b>Task 1: Hospital Management System Design</b>
                <p>Design a fully normalized database for a hospital with:</p>
                
                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 15px; margin: 15px 0;">
                    <div>
                        <h5 style="margin-top: 0;">Core Entities:</h5>
                        <ul style="font-size: 14px;">
                            <li>Patients (personal info, medical history)</li>
                            <li>Doctors (specialization, schedule, qualifications)</li>
                            <li>Nurses (wards, shifts)</li>
                            <li>Appointments (date, time, status)</li>
                            <li>Medical Records (diagnoses, treatments)</li>
                            <li>Prescriptions (medications, dosage)</li>
                            <li>Wards/Rooms (types, availability)</li>
                            <li>Billing (insurance, payments)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div>
                        <h5 style="margin-top: 0;">Complex Relationships:</h5>
                        <ul style="font-size: 14px;">
                            <li>A patient can have multiple doctors</li>
                            <li>A doctor can see multiple patients</li>
                            <li>Multiple medications per prescription</li>
                            <li>Family medical history tracking</li>
                            <li>Insurance claims processing</li>
                            <li>Lab test results tracking</li>
                            <li>Surgery team assignments</li>
                            <li>Equipment usage tracking</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <b>Requirements:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Create ERD diagram with all relationships</li>
                    <li>Write CREATE TABLE statements for at least 10 tables</li>
                    <li>Implement proper primary and foreign keys</li>
                    <li>Apply 1NF, 2NF, and 3NF</li>
                    <li>Consider BCNF where applicable</li>
                    <li>Insert realistic sample data</li>
                    <li>Write queries that demonstrate the relationships</li>
                </ul>
                
                <b>Task 2: Performance Optimization Analysis</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify 3 places where denormalization would improve performance</li>
                    <li>Design materialized views for common reports</li>
                    <li>Suggest indexing strategy for your design</li>
                    <li>Estimate storage requirements for 5 years of data</li>
                    <li>Design partitioning strategy for large tables</li>
                </ul>
                
                <b>Task 3: Migration Strategy</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Design a migration plan from an old unnormalized system</li>
                    <li>Create scripts to transform existing data</li>
                    <li>Design rollback procedures</li>
                    <li>Create data validation scripts</li>
                    <li>Design performance testing procedures</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h3>Key Learning Points for Day 3:</h3>

            <ol>
                <li><b>Normalization Principles:</b> 1NF, 2NF, 3NF, and when to apply each</li>
                <li><b>Primary Key Strategies:</b> Natural vs surrogate keys, composite keys, UUIDs</li>
                <li><b>Foreign Key Design:</b> Establishing and maintaining referential integrity</li>
                <li><b>Relationship Types:</b> One-to-one, one-to-many, many-to-many implementations</li>
                <li><b>Data Integrity:</b> Preventing anomalies through proper design</li>
                <li><b>Performance Trade-offs:</b> When to normalize vs when to denormalize</li>
                <li><b>Schema Evolution:</b> Designing databases that can grow and change</li>
                <li><b>Best Practices:</b> Naming conventions, documentation, and maintenance</li>
            </ol>

            <div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h3>üí° Database Design Wisdom:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Start Normalized:</b> Begin with 3NF, then denormalize only for proven performance needs</li>
                    <li><b>Think in Sets:</b> Relational databases work with sets of data, not individual records</li>
                    <li><b>Design for Change:</b> Business requirements evolve - make your schema adaptable</li>
                    <li><b>Document Everything:</b> Future you (and other developers) will thank you</li>
                    <li><b>Test with Real Data:</b> Your design should handle real-world data volumes and patterns</li>
                    <li><b>Consider Access Patterns:</b> Design for how data will be queried, not just how it's stored</li>
                    <li><b>Plan for Growth:</b> What works for 1000 records may not work for 1 million</li>
                    <li><b>Security by Design:</b> Consider data privacy and access controls from the beginning</li>
                    <li><b>Backup Strategy:</b> Design with recovery in mind - test your backup procedures</li>
                    <li><b>Performance Monitoring:</b> Build in monitoring from day one</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 20px 0; border-left: 5px solid #3498db;">
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #2c3e50;">üîÆ What's Next?</h3>
                <p><b>Tomorrow (Day 4):</b> We'll master phpMyAdmin and database management tools. You'll learn:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Complete phpMyAdmin interface tour and features</li>
                    <li>Importing and exporting databases</li>
                    <li>User management and permissions</li>
                    <li>Database optimization and maintenance</li>
                    <li>Backup and recovery strategies</li>
                    <li>Monitoring and performance tuning</li>
                    <li>Troubleshooting common issues</li>
                    <li>Security best practices</li>
                </ul>
                <p><b>Pro Tip:</b> The best database design is one that balances normalization for integrity with strategic denormalization for performance. Always document your design decisions!</p>
            </div>

            <p><b>Remember:</b> Good database design is an art and a science. It requires understanding both theoretical principles and practical constraints. Your design decisions will impact application performance, maintainability, and scalability for years to come!</p>`
            },
            "11-4": {
                icon: "fa-tools",
                title: "Using phpMyAdmin to Manage Data",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 4: Using phpMyAdmin to Manage Data</h1>
        <p>Today we'll master phpMyAdmin, the most popular web-based MySQL administration tool. You'll learn how to efficiently manage databases, users, backups, and optimize performance through a graphical interface.</p>

        <div class="analogy-box">
            <b>Analogy: The Database Control Room üéÆ</b><br/>
            
            phpMyAdmin: Mission control dashboard for your databases<br/>
            Database: A spaceship (your application data)<br/>
            Tables: Different compartments of the spaceship<br/>
            SQL Console: Direct communication with the spaceship computer<br/>
            Import/Export: Loading/unloading cargo from the spaceship<br/>
            User Management: Issuing security badges for crew members<br/>
            Backups: Creating emergency escape pods with data copies<br/>
            Optimization: Tuning the engines for maximum performance
        </div>

        <h3>Getting Started with phpMyAdmin</h3>

        <b>Accessing and Navigating phpMyAdmin:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // Typical Access URLs:
        Local XAMPP: http://localhost/phpmyadmin
        Local WAMP: http://localhost/phpmyadmin
        Local MAMP: http://localhost:8888/phpmyadmin
        Remote Hosting: http://yourdomain.com/phpmyadmin

        // Default Credentials (Change these in production!):
        XAMPP: Username: root, Password: (blank)
        WAMP: Username: root, Password: (blank)
        MAMP: Username: root, Password: root
        cPanel: Use provided credentials

        // First Steps:
        1. Login with your credentials
        2. Check phpMyAdmin version (bottom right corner)
        3. Familiarize yourself with the interface:
        - Left sidebar: Database list
        - Top navigation: Tabs for different operations
        - Main area: Content specific to selected item
        4. Check server status and variables
        5. Review current connections and processes
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>phpMyAdmin Interface Tour</h3>

        <div style="background-color: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; border: 2px solid #4A90E2; margin: 20px 0;">
            <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr; gap: 20px;">
                <!-- Left Sidebar -->
                <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; border: 1px solid #dee2e6;">
                    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #495057;">üìÇ Left Sidebar</h4>
                    <div style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 13px;">
                        <div style="padding: 5px; background: #e9ecef; margin: 2px 0; border-radius: 3px;">
                            <b>Server: localhost</b>
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 5px; margin: 2px 0; color: #6c757d;">
                            ‚ñ∫ information_schema
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 5px; margin: 2px 0; color: #6c757d;">
                            ‚ñ∫ mysql
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 5px; margin: 2px 0; color: #6c757d;">
                            ‚ñ∫ performance_schema
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 5px; background: #e7f1ff; margin: 2px 0; border-radius: 3px; color: #0066cc;">
                            <b>‚ñ∫ finance_app</b>
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 15px; font-size: 12px;">
                            <div>‚úì users</div>
                            <div>‚úì transactions</div>
                            <div>‚úì categories</div>
                            <div>‚úì savings_goals</div>
                            <div>‚úì budgets</div>
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 5px; margin: 2px 0; color: #6c757d;">
                            ‚ñ∫ test_db
                        </div>
                        <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 5px; background: #f8f9fa; border-top: 1px solid #dee2e6;">
                            <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #6c757d;">New Database</div>
                            <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #6c757d;">Logout</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Main Content Area -->
                <div>
                    <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px 5px 0 0; border: 1px solid #dee2e6; border-bottom: none;">
                        <div style="display: flex; gap: 10px;">
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #fff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px;">Structure</div>
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #e7f1ff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px; font-weight: bold;">SQL</div>
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #fff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px;">Search</div>
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #fff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px;">Insert</div>
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #fff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px;">Export</div>
                            <div style="padding: 5px 10px; background: #fff; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 13px;">More</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border: 1px solid #dee2e6; border-radius: 0 0 5px 5px;">
                        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #495057;">üìù SQL Query Window</h4>
                        <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; font-family: monospace; font-size: 14px;">
                            SELECT * FROM users WHERE user_id = 1;
                        </div>
                        <div style="margin-top: 10px; text-align: right;">
                            <button style="padding: 8px 16px; background: #28a745; color: white; border: none; border-radius: 3px; cursor: pointer;">Go</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div style="margin-top: 20px; padding-top: 15px; border-top: 1px dashed #ddd; font-size: 12px; color: #6c757d; text-align: center;">
                phpMyAdmin Interface Overview - Main Navigation Areas
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Database Operations</h3>

        <b>Creating and Managing Databases:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // 1. Creating a New Database
        Steps:
        1. Click "New" in left sidebar
        2. Enter database name: "ecommerce_db"
        3. Select collation: "utf8mb4_unicode_ci" (recommended for multilingual)
        4. Click "Create"

        // 2. Viewing Database Information
        - Click database name in left sidebar
        - See overview of tables, size, rows
        - Check collation and privileges

        // 3. Renaming Database (phpMyAdmin method)
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Operations" tab
        3. Enter new name in "Rename database to"
        4. Click "Go"
        Note: Actually creates copy and drops old one

        // 4. Copying Database
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Operations" tab
        3. In "Copy database to" section:
        - Enter new name: "ecommerce_db_backup"
        - Select "structure and data"
        - Check "Add AUTO_INCREMENT value"
        4. Click "Go"

        // 5. Dropping (Deleting) Database
        ‚ö†Ô∏è WARNING: This cannot be undone! ‚ö†Ô∏è
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Operations" tab
        3. Click red "Drop the database" button
        4. Confirm by typing database name
        5. Click "Yes"

        // 6. Database Statistics
        Check:
        - Total tables
        - Total rows
        - Total size
        - Index size
        - Overhead (can be repaired)
        - Collation used

        // 7. Repair and Optimize
        For MyISAM tables (not InnoDB):
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Operations" tab
        3. Check all tables
        4. Select "Repair table" or "Optimize table"
        5. Click "Go"

        // 8. Changing Collation
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Operations" tab
        3. Find "Collation" section
        4. Select new collation
        5. Choose option:
        - Change all tables collations
        - Change all tables columns collations
        6. Click "Go"
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Table Operations</h3>

        <b>Managing Tables Through phpMyAdmin:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // 1. Creating a Table (GUI Method)
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Click "New" tab or "Create table"
        3. Enter table name: "products"
        4. Enter number of columns: 6
        5. Click "Go"
        6. For each column:
        - Name: "product_id"
        - Type: INT
        - Length/Values: (blank for INT)
        - Default: None
        - Collation: (blank for INT)
        - Attributes: UNSIGNED
        - Null: ‚òê (not checked)
        - Index: PRIMARY
        - A_I: ‚òë (Auto Increment)
        - Comments: "Unique product identifier"
        7. Set table options:
        - Storage Engine: InnoDB
        - Collation: utf8mb4_unicode_ci
        8. Click "Save"

        // 2. Viewing Table Structure
        Steps:
        1. Click table name in left sidebar
        2. Go to "Structure" tab
        3. See all columns with details:
        - Type, Null, Default, Extra
        - Browse indexes, foreign keys
        - Space usage, row format

        // 3. Modifying Table Structure
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Structure" tab
        2. Use actions on each column:
        - Change: Modify column definition
        - Drop: Remove column (dangerous!)
        - Primary: Set as primary key
        - Unique: Set as unique index
        - Index: Create index
        - Fulltext: Create fulltext index
        - Spatial: Create spatial index

        // 4. Adding New Column
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Structure" tab
        2. Scroll to bottom "Add column(s)"
        3. Enter: 1 column(s)
        4. Choose: At End of Table / After specific column
        5. Click "Go"
        6. Define new column as in step 1

        // 5. Table Operations Tab
        Important operations:
        - Rename table
        - Move table to different database
        - Copy table (structure, data, or both)
        - Table maintenance (analyze, check, repair, optimize)
        - Empty table (truncate)
        - Drop table

        // 6. Table Maintenance Commands
        ANALYZE TABLE products;  -- Update index statistics
        CHECK TABLE products;    -- Check for errors
        REPAIR TABLE products;   -- Repair MyISAM tables
        OPTIMIZE TABLE products; -- Reclaim unused space

        // 7. Viewing Table Relations
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Structure" tab
        2. Click "Relation view"
        3. See foreign key relationships
        4. Add/edit foreign key constraints

        // 8. Importing Table Structure from SQL
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Import" tab
        2. Choose file or paste SQL
        3. Format: SQL
        4. Click "Go"
        Example SQL:
        CREATE TABLE customers (
            customer_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
            name VARCHAR(100),
            email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE
        );
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Data Manipulation</h3>

        <b>Working with Data Through the Interface:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // 1. Browsing Data
        Steps:
        1. Click table name
        2. Go to "Browse" tab
        3. See paginated results (30 rows per page default)
        4. Use navigation: First, Previous, Next, Last
        5. Options:
        - Sort by clicking column headers
        - Filter using "Show search criteria"
        - Edit/Delete individual rows

        // 2. Searching Data
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Search" tab
        2. For each search column:
        - Select column
        - Operator: =, >, <, LIKE, BETWEEN, etc.
        - Value: Enter search value
        3. Options:
        - Logical operator: AND/OR
        - Insensitive search
        - Use wildcards: % (any chars), _ (single char)
        4. Click "Go"

        // 3. Inserting Data (Form)
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Insert" tab
        2. Two forms appear (for inserting 2 rows)
        3. Fill values for each column
        4. Options:
        - Ignore: Skip on duplicate key
        - Use function: NOW(), UUID(), etc.
        5. Click "Go"

        // 4. Inserting Multiple Rows (SQL)
        Steps:
        1. Go to "SQL" tab
        2. Enter:
        INSERT INTO users (username, email) VALUES
        ('user1', 'user1@example.com'),
        ('user2', 'user2@example.com'),
        ('user3', 'user3@example.com');
        3. Click "Go"

        // 5. Updating Data
        Method 1: Edit individual row
        1. Browse table
        2. Click "Edit" pencil icon
        3. Modify values
        4. Click "Go"

        Method 2: Update multiple rows
        1. Browse table
        2. Check rows to edit
        3. Click "Change" link above results
        4. Modify common values
        5. Click "Go"

        Method 3: SQL UPDATE
        1. Go to "SQL" tab
        2. Enter:
        UPDATE users 
        SET last_login = NOW() 
        WHERE last_login IS NULL;
        3. Click "Go"

        // 6. Deleting Data
        Method 1: Delete individual row
        1. Browse table
        2. Click "Delete" trash icon
        3. Confirm

        Method 2: Delete multiple rows
        1. Browse table
        2. Check rows to delete
        3. Click "Delete" link above results
        4. Confirm

        Method 3: SQL DELETE
        1. Go to "SQL" tab
        2. Enter:
        DELETE FROM temp_sessions 
        WHERE created_at < DATE_SUB(NOW(), INTERVAL 24 HOUR);
        3. Click "Go"

        // 7. Emptying Table (Truncate)
        ‚ö†Ô∏è Faster than DELETE, cannot be rolled back!
        Steps:
        1. Go to "Operations" tab
        2. Click "Empty the table (TRUNCATE)"
        3. Confirm

        // 8. Exporting Query Results
        Steps:
        1. Run any SELECT query
        2. Scroll to bottom of results
        3. Click "Export"
        4. Choose format: CSV, JSON, Excel, etc.
        5. Configure options
        6. Click "Go"
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Import and Export</h3>

        <b>Data Transfer Operations:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // 1. Exporting Database
        Steps:
        1. Select database
        2. Go to "Export" tab
        3. Choose method: Quick / Custom
        4. Quick export:
        - Format: SQL (recommended)
        - Click "Go"

        5. Custom export options:
        - Tables: Select specific tables
        - Output: Save to file / View as text
        - Format: SQL, CSV, JSON, Excel, etc.
        - SQL options:
            * Add DROP TABLE / VIEW / PROCEDURE
            * Add CREATE DATABASE
            * Add AUTO_INCREMENT value
            * Enclose in transaction
            * Disable foreign key checks
        - Data creation options:
            * Complete inserts
            * Extended inserts (faster)
            * Max length of created query
        - Click "Go"

        // 2. Exporting Single Table
        Steps:
        1. Select table
        2. Go to "Export" tab
        3. Similar options as database export
        4. Additional format-specific options for CSV, Excel, etc.

        // 3. Importing Database
        Steps:
        1. Select target database
        2. Go to "Import" tab
        3. Choose file (Max: usually 50-100MB)
        4. Format: Auto-detect or select
        5. Character set: utf8 (usually correct)
        6. Partial import: Skip queries number
        7. Format-specific options:
        - SQL: Enable foreign key checks
        - CSV: Specify columns, separators
        8. Click "Go"

        // 4. Handling Large Exports/Imports
        For files > 100MB:
        Option A: Command line (recommended)
        Export: mysqldump -u root -p database > backup.sql
        Import: mysql -u root -p database < backup.sql

        Option B: Split SQL file
        Split: split -l 1000 largefile.sql part_
        Import parts sequentially

        Option C: Increase php limits
        In php.ini:
        upload_max_filesize = 500M
        post_max_size = 500M
        max_execution_time = 300

        // 5. CSV Import/Export
        CSV Export:
        1. Go to "Export" tab
        2. Format: CSV
        3. Options:
        - Columns separated with: , (comma)
        - Columns enclosed with: " (double quote)
        - Columns escaped with: \ (backslash)
        - Replace NULL with: NULL
        - Put fields names in first row: ‚úì

        CSV Import:
        1. Go to "Import" tab
        2. Format: CSV
        3. Options:
        - Columns separated by: , (comma)
        - Columns enclosed by: " (double quote)
        - Columns escaped by: \ (backslash)
        - Lines terminated by: auto
        - Column names: (first line if header)

        // 6. JSON Export/Import
        JSON Export:
        1. Format: JSON
        2. Options pretty print for readability

        JSON Import:
        1. MySQL 5.7+ supports JSON import
        2. Usually import as SQL with JSON functions
        3. Or parse JSON in application layer

        // 7. Export Profiles
        Save common export settings:
        1. Configure export options
        2. Click "Save export profile"
        3. Name: "Daily backup"
        4. Options to save
        5. Later: Load from saved profile

        // 8. Scheduled Backups (cron)
        Shell script example:
        #!/bin/bash
        mysqldump -u root -pPASSWORD finance_app > /backups/finance_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql
        gzip /backups/finance_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql
        find /backups -name "*.sql.gz" -mtime +30 -delete

        Add to crontab (daily at 2 AM):
        0 2 * * * /path/to/backup_script.sh
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>User Management and Privileges</h3>

        <b>Managing Database Users and Permissions:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // 1. Viewing Current Users
        Steps:
        1. Click "User accounts" tab (main page)
        2. See all users with:
        - Username and host
        - Global privileges
        - Grant option

        // 2. Creating New User
        Steps:
        1. Click "User accounts" tab
        2. Click "Add user account"
        3. Login Information:
        - User name: app_user
        - Host name: Local / Any host / Use text field
            * localhost (local connections only)
            * % (any host - less secure)
            * 192.168.1.% (IP range)
        - Password: Generate / Set
        - Authentication plugin: mysql_native_password

        4. Global privileges:
        - Data: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
        - Structure: CREATE, ALTER, INDEX, DROP
        - Administration: Usually none for app users
        - Select all for specific category

        5. Click "Go"

        // 3. Editing User Privileges
        Steps:
        1. Click "User accounts" tab
        2. Click "Edit privileges" for user
        3. Global privileges: Modify as needed
        4. Database-specific privileges:
        - Click "Database" section
        - Select database
        - Set privileges for that database only
        5. Click "Go"

        // 4. Database-Specific Privileges
        Common setups:
        1. Application user (read/write):
        - SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
        - EXECUTE (for stored procedures)
        - LOCK TABLES (if needed)

        2. Reporting user (read-only):
        - SELECT only
        - SHOW VIEW

        3. Admin user (full access):
        - ALL PRIVILEGES
        - WITH GRANT OPTION (careful!)

        4. Backup user:
        - SELECT, LOCK TABLES, RELOAD
        - SHOW DATABASES, PROCESS

        // 5. Revoking Privileges
        Steps:
        1. Edit user privileges
        2. Uncheck privileges to revoke
        3. Click "Go"

        // 6. Removing Users
        Steps:
        1. Click "User accounts" tab
        2. Check user to remove
        3. Click "Remove selected users"
        4. Confirm removal
        5. Options:
        - Drop databases with same name
        - Revoke active privileges

        // 7. Login Without Password (Not Recommended)
        If you lose root password:
        1. Stop MySQL service
        2. Start MySQL with --skip-grant-tables
        3. Connect without password
        4. Update mysql.user table
        5. Flush privileges
        6. Restart normally

        // 8. Best Practices for User Management
        1. Principle of least privilege
        2. Use different users for different purposes
        3. Avoid using root for applications
        4. Regularly review user privileges
        5. Use strong passwords
        6. Limit host access (% only when necessary)
        7. Monitor failed login attempts
        8. Remove unused accounts
        </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Advanced Features</h3>

        <b>phpMyAdmin Power Features:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
