        <h3>Security Best Practices</h3>

        <b>Securing Your phpMyAdmin Installation:</b>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
        // ‚ö†Ô∏è IMPORTANT: phpMyAdmin Security Checklist ‚ö†Ô∏è

        // 1. Change Default Credentials
        Immediately after installation:
        - Change root password
        - Remove anonymous users
        - Remove test database

        SQL:
        ALTER USER 'root'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'StrongPassword123!';
        DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS test;
        DELETE FROM mysql.user WHERE User='';

        // 2. Restrict Access by IP
        Edit phpMyAdmin config (/etc/phpmyadmin/config.inc.php):
        $cfg['Servers'][$i]['AllowDeny']['order'] = 'deny,allow';
        $cfg['Servers'][$i]['AllowDeny']['rules'] = array(
            'deny from all',
            'allow from 192.168.1.0/24',  // Your local network
            'allow from 203.0.113.5',      // Your static IP
        );

        // 3. Use HTTPS Only
        Force SSL in config:
        $cfg['ForceSSL'] = true;

        Apache config:
        <Directory /usr/share/phpmyadmin>
            SSLRequireSSL
        </Directory>

        // 4. Rename phpMyAdmin Directory
        Rename from "phpmyadmin" to something random:
        sudo mv /var/www/html/phpmyadmin /var/www/html/dbadmin_xyz123

        // 5. Set Up .htaccess Protection
        Create /phpmyadmin/.htaccess:
        AuthType Basic
        AuthName "Restricted Access"
        AuthUserFile /etc/phpmyadmin/.htpasswd
        Require valid-user

        Create password file:
        htpasswd -c /etc/phpmyadmin/.htpasswd admin

        // 6. Limit Login Attempts
        Install Fail2Ban:
        sudo apt install fail2ban
        sudo nano /etc/fail2ban/jail.local

        Add:
        [phpmyadmin]
        enabled = true
        port = http,https
        filter = phpmyadmin
        logpath = /var/log/apache2/error.log
        maxretry = 3
        bantime = 3600

        // 7. Regular Updates
        Keep updated:
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade phpmyadmin

        // 8. Disable Root Login Remotely
        MySQL config (/etc/mysql/mysql.conf.d/mysqld.cnf):
        [mysqld]
        skip-networking  # Disable remote connections
        # or
        bind-address = 127.0.0.1  # Local only

        // 9. Audit Logging
        Enable MySQL audit plugin or use:
        CREATE TABLE security_log (
            id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
            username VARCHAR(50),
            action VARCHAR(50),
            table_name VARCHAR(100),
            query TEXT,
            ip_address VARCHAR(45),
            timestamp TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
        );

        // 10. Backup Configuration
        Regularly backup:
        - Database backups
        - phpMyAdmin configuration
        - SSL certificates
        - .htaccess files

        // 11. Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
        phpMyAdmin supports 2FA:
        1. Install required PHP extensions
        2. Enable in config:
        $cfg['Auth_2FA'] = 'google';
        3. Users set up in their accounts

        // 12. Security Scanning Tools
        Regularly scan:
        - MySQL: mysql_secure_installation
        - PHP: php -l (lint check)
        - Web: Nikto, OWASP ZAP
        - SSL: SSL Labs test
        </pre>
