            "12-1": {
                icon: "fa-plug",
                title: "Connecting PHP to MySQL (PDO/MySQLi)",
                html: `<h1>Week 12, Day 1: Connecting PHP to MySQL (PDO/MySQLi)</h1>
<p>Today we bridge the gap between frontend and backend! We'll learn how to connect PHP to MySQL databases using both PDO and MySQLi extensions, understand their differences, and build secure database connections.</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: The Bridge Between Two Cities üåâ</b><br/>
    
    PHP: Your home city (application logic)<br/>
    MySQL: The database city (data storage)<br/>
    PDO/MySQLi: Different bridge designs to connect the cities<br/>
    Connection: The actual bridge structure<br/>
    Prepared Statements: Security checkpoints on the bridge<br/>
    Transactions: Coordinated convoy systems<br/>
    Error Handling: Bridge inspectors and maintenance crews<br/>
    Connection Pooling: Multiple lanes for traffic flow
</div>

<h3>Understanding Database Connection Options</h3>

<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 5px solid #4A90E2;">
    <h4>üìä PDO vs MySQLi: Which Should You Choose?</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); border: 2px solid #3498db;">
            <h5 style="color: #3498db; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 2px solid #3498db; padding-bottom: 10px;">üîµ PDO (PHP Data Objects)</h5>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Database Support:</strong> Multiple (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLite, etc.)</li>
                <li><strong>API Style:</strong> Object-oriented (also procedural available)</li>
                <li><strong>Named Parameters:</strong> Yes (:name, :email)</li>
                <li><strong>Prepared Statements:</strong> Emulated or native</li>
                <li><strong>Error Handling:</strong> Exception-based</li>
                <li><strong>Transactions:</strong> Consistent across databases</li>
                <li><strong>Best For:</strong> Multi-database projects, OOP lovers</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); border: 2px solid #27ae60;">
            <h5 style="color: #27ae60; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 2px solid #27ae60; padding-bottom: 10px;">üü¢ MySQLi (MySQL Improved)</h5>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Database Support:</strong> MySQL only</li>
                <li><strong>API Style:</strong> Both OOP and procedural</li>
                <li><strong>Named Parameters:</strong> No (only positional ?)</li>
                <li><strong>Prepared Statements:</strong> Always native</li>
                <li><strong>Error Handling:</strong> Mixed (exceptions or error codes)</li>
                <li><strong>Transactions:</strong> MySQL-specific</li>
                <li><strong>Best For:</strong> MySQL-only projects, procedural code</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 15px; background: #fff3cd; border-radius: 5px; border: 1px solid #ffeaa7;">
        <h5 style="color: #856404; margin-top: 0;">üéØ Recommendation for This Course:</h5>
        <p>We'll use <strong>PDO</strong> because:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>It's more future-proof (supports multiple databases)</li>
            <li>Cleaner object-oriented syntax</li>
            <li>Better error handling with exceptions</li>
            <li>Named parameters make code more readable</li>
            <li>Industry standard for new projects</li>
        </ol>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Setting Up Database Configuration</h3>

<b>Secure Configuration File (config/database.php):</b>
