            "13-1": {
                icon: "fa-globe",
                title: "Domains, DNS, and Nameservers",
                html: `<h1>Week 13, Day 1: Domains, DNS, and Nameservers</h1>
    <p>Today we'll learn how the internet routes traffic to your website through domains, DNS, and nameservers.</p>
    
    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: The Internet as a Global Postal System üìÆüåê</b><br/>
        
        Domain Name: Your home address (123 Main St)<br/>
        IP Address: GPS coordinates (latitude/longitude)<br/>
        DNS: The phone book that maps addresses to coordinates<br/>
        Nameserver: The librarian who looks up addresses in the phone book<br/>
        DNS Record: An entry in the phone book<br/>
        Registrar: The government office that issues addresses<br/>
        Hosting: The physical house at your address<br/>
        Propagation: Time for new phone books to reach all post offices
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>What is a domain name?</li>
        <li>Domain name structure (TLD, SLD, subdomain)</li>
        <li>How DNS works (resolution process)</li>
        <li>Types of DNS records (A, CNAME, MX, TXT, etc.)</li>
        <li>Nameservers and their role</li>
        <li>Domain registration process</li>
        <li>DNS propagation and TTL</li>
        <li>Common DNS tools (nslookup, dig, whois)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>In-Depth Explanation</h3>
    
    <b>a. Domain Name Structure</b><br/>
    
    <b>Anatomy of a Domain Name:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            https://www.example.com
            |         |       |    |
            Protocol  |    Domain  TLD
                      |
                    Subdomain
            
            Full breakdown:
            
            Protocol: https:// (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)
            Subdomain: www (World Wide Web - traditional but optional)
            Second-Level Domain (SLD): example (your chosen name)
            Top-Level Domain (TLD): .com (Commercial)
            
            Other common TLDs:
            ‚Ä¢ .com - Commercial
            ‚Ä¢ .org - Organizations
            ‚Ä¢ .net - Network
            ‚Ä¢ .edu - Education
            ‚Ä¢ .gov - Government
            ‚Ä¢ Country codes: .us, .uk, .ca, .au, etc.
            ‚Ä¢ New gTLDs: .app, .blog, .shop, .dev, etc.
            
            Subdomain examples:
            ‚Ä¢ blog.example.com
            ‚Ä¢ shop.example.com
            ‚Ä¢ api.example.com
            ‚Ä¢ mail.example.com
            ‚Ä¢ test.example.com
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Domain Hierarchy:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>Root Domain</b>: . (the dot at the end - usually invisible)<br/>
        <b>Top-Level Domains (TLDs)</b>: .com, .org, .net, .uk, etc.<br/>
        <b>Second-Level Domains (SLDs)</b>: example in example.com<br/>
        <b>Third-Level Domains (Subdomains)</b>: www, blog, shop, etc.<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN)</b>: www.example.com.<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Includes all parts including the trailing dot (root)<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Maximum length: 253 characters total<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Each label (between dots): max 63 characters<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Allowed characters: a-z, 0-9, hyphen (not at start/end)
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>b. How DNS Works - Step by Step</b><br/>
    
    <b>DNS Resolution Process:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            User types "www.example.com" in browser:
            
            1. <b>Browser Cache Check</b>
                ‚Ä¢ Browser checks its own cache for the DNS record
                ‚Ä¢ If found, skip to step 8
            
            2. <b>Operating System Cache Check</b>
                ‚Ä¢ Browser asks OS (Windows/Mac/Linux) for DNS record
                ‚Ä¢ OS checks its DNS resolver cache
                ‚Ä¢ If found, skip to step 8
            
            3. <b>Router Cache Check</b>
                ‚Ä¢ Request goes to local router
                ‚Ä¢ Router checks its cache
                ‚Ä¢ If found, skip to step 8
            
            4. <b>ISP DNS Resolver</b>
                ‚Ä¢ Request reaches ISP's DNS servers
                ‚Ä¢ ISP checks its cache
                ‚Ä¢ If not found, begins recursive query
            
            5. <b>Root Nameservers</b> (13 globally distributed)
                ‚Ä¢ ISP asks root server: "Where is .com?"
                ‚Ä¢ Root responds: "Ask these TLD nameservers"
            
            6. <b>TLD Nameservers</b>
                ‚Ä¢ ISP asks .com nameserver: "Where is example.com?"
                ‚Ä¢ TLD responds: "Ask these authoritative nameservers"
            
            7. <b>Authoritative Nameservers</b>
                ‚Ä¢ ISP asks example.com's nameservers
                ‚Ä¢ Authoritative server responds with IP address: "93.184.216.34"
            
            8. <b>Response Travels Back</b>
                ‚Ä¢ IP address cached at each step (ISP, router, OS, browser)
                ‚Ä¢ Browser receives IP address
            
            9. <b>HTTP Request</b>
                ‚Ä¢ Browser sends HTTP request to IP address 93.184.216.34
                ‚Ä¢ Server responds with website content
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <b>Visual Representation of DNS Flow:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        1. User ‚Üí Browser ‚Üí OS ‚Üí Router ‚Üí ISP DNS<br/>
        2. ISP DNS ‚Üí Root Nameserver<br/>
        3. Root ‚Üí TLD Nameserver (.com)<br/>
        4. TLD ‚Üí Authoritative Nameserver (example.com)<br/>
        5. Authoritative ‚Üí ISP DNS (IP address)<br/>
        6. ISP DNS ‚Üí Router ‚Üí OS ‚Üí Browser<br/>
        7. Browser ‚Üí Web Server (HTTP request)<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>Time To Live (TTL)</b>: How long each step caches the DNS record<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Typically 1 hour to 48 hours<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Lower TTL = faster changes propagate<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Higher TTL = less DNS traffic, faster resolution
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>c. DNS Record Types</b><br/>
    
    <b>Essential DNS Records:</b>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background-color: #f0f0f0;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Record Type</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Purpose</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Example</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">TTL</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">A (Address)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Maps domain to IPv4 address</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">example.com ‚Üí 93.184.216.34</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">AAAA</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Maps domain to IPv6 address</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">example.com ‚Üí 2606:2800:220:1:248:1893:25c8:1946</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">CNAME (Canonical Name)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Alias for another domain</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">www ‚Üí example.com</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">MX (Mail Exchange)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Directs email to mail servers</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Priority 10 ‚Üí mail.example.com</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">TXT (Text)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Verification, SPF, DKIM, DMARC</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">"v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com ~all"</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">NS (Nameserver)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Authoritative nameservers</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">ns1.cloudflare.com, ns2.cloudflare.com</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">48 hours</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">SOA (Start of Authority)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Zone information, primary nameserver</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Administrative details</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">PTR (Pointer)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reverse DNS - IP to domain</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">93.184.216.34 ‚Üí example.com</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">SRV (Service)</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Location of specific services</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">_sip._tcp.example.com ‚Üí server details</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">1 hour</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    
    <b>Example DNS Zone File:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <pre>
            ; Zone file for example.com
            $TTL 3600       ; Default TTL: 1 hour
            
            @ IN SOA ns1.example.com. admin.example.com. (
                2024011501 ; Serial number (YYYYMMDDNN)
                7200       ; Refresh (2 hours)
                3600       ; Retry (1 hour)
                1209600    ; Expire (2 weeks)
                3600       ; Minimum TTL (1 hour)
            )
            
            ; Nameservers
            @       IN NS   ns1.example.com.
            @       IN NS   ns2.example.com.
            
            ; A Records (IPv4)
            @       IN A    93.184.216.34     ; example.com
            www     IN A    93.184.216.34     ; www.example.com
            mail    IN A    203.0.113.1       ; mail.example.com
            
            ; CNAME Records (Aliases)
            blog    IN CNAME example.com.     ; blog.example.com
            shop    IN CNAME example.com.     ; shop.example.com
            
            ; MX Records (Mail servers - lower number = higher priority)
            @       IN MX 10 mail.example.com.
            @       IN MX 20 mail2.example.com.
            
            ; TXT Records
            @       IN TXT "v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com ~all"
            @       IN TXT "google-site-verification=abc123"
            
            ; SRV Records (for specific services)
            _sip._tcp   IN SRV 10 60 5060 sipserver.example.com.
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <hr/>
    
    <b>d. Nameservers and Registrars</b><br/>
    
    <b>Domain Registration Process:</b>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <b>1. Choose a Domain Registrar</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ GoDaddy, Namecheap, Google Domains, Cloudflare<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Compare prices, features, and support<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>2. Check Domain Availability</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Search for your desired domain<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Try different TLDs if .com is taken<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Consider alternative spellings<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>3. Register the Domain</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Provide contact information (WHOIS)<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Choose registration period (1-10 years)<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Enable privacy protection (hides WHOIS info)<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Pay for registration<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>4. Configure Nameservers</b><br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Default: Registrar's nameservers<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Custom: Your hosting provider's nameservers<br/>
        ‚Ä¢ Advanced: Cloudflare, AWS Route 53, etc.<br/>
        <br/>
        <b>5. Set Up DNS Records</b><br/>
